text:
I've been going to Pita Pit for 16 years and the quality has remained the same for the entire time. I was beyond excited to see one opened up on Oahu! The only crime here is its not open u til 3 am like the one in my old college town with a bogo on the whole menu after 11pm!
Coming off memory lane, they have all fresh ingredients and premium meats! I like that they feature vegetarian options for the whole menu! I miss the Huberts lemonade they sold at this location, but they still have fountain drinks and other bottled drinks. A must stop before a waikiki beach day or after a trip to the zoo! Definitely try this place for its inexpensive couture fares and I know you will go back! 16 years from now, you could be telling your own stories down memory lane!
business_description: Diners create their own sandwiches at this health-oriented counter-serve chain.

Thank you to Melanie and all of the workers for such warm, friendly and quality service!

text: If I could give this 0 stars I would. The customer service is absolutely terrible. I placed an order for three pizzas and received a call forty minutes later saying they had messed up two of my pizzas which had to be remade. It was a delay but understandable as mistakes happen, however, we requested that the third pizza be remade because we didn't want two fresh pizzas with one that had been sitting for almost an hour. The manager said there is no way they would do that but could offer us a brownie. I asked the manager that even though THEY messed up they wouldn't remake the pizza and he said no we dont do that. ( I feel sorry for whoever gets that one) I told them they can cancel the order to which the manager replied with a sigh and hung up. This was completely unprofessional how the manager reacted to us wanting a fresh third pizza with the other two. The manager displayed a complete disregard for the customer, and lack of leadership qualities. We will not order from this pizza hut anymore.

text:
I felt it was a little overpriced, but that's somewhat to be expected of resort dining.

My larger issue was that the menu didn't represent what we were served.  My wife's dish was supposed to have mushrooms and spinach. There was hardly any spinach and it had broccolini and green peppers. My dish was supposed to have local vegetables and had broccolini but also had mushrooms, which I don't consider a vegetable, and I picked the dish because it didn't list mushrooms as an ingredient.

I was also surprised that there was no option to add cheese or cracked pepper to the pasta.

That said, once we picked out what we didn't want the food tasted very good. My son's pizza was delicious.

EDIT: We got grab and go breakfast and it lowered my review. The croissant sandwich was supposed to have cheddar cheese but had american instead. Both my son and I were greatly displeased. AGAIN the menu didn't match the food delivered.  This is a MAJOR problem.

In addition, the english muffin on my wife's sandwich wasn't toasted, which is lazy and lame.

text: We were so delighted to find an Italian restaurant with focaccia like we had in Rome! The lobster chowder was excellent and was big enough for us to share. It would have been better had they provided two little strips of foccacia to go with it, knowing that we were intending on sharing it before our main meal. My husband had the foresight to order the foccacia separately. We also enjoyed the pepperoni and salami Roman pizza. This pizza was plenty big enough at the smaller portion or half size for us to eat and take some home. The crust is thick but it is so full of wonderful air bubbles that it doesn't seem like you're eating a brick as some focaccias do. I don't particularly like salami but this was really tasty and lean. It's important to know that the restaurant is at the opposite end of the resort from the entrance. The valet parking is free if you're using that restaurant, which is a real plus considering the cost of parking around the Hilton. Take the tram to the restaurant if you have any issues with walking. If not you can walk to the right, down a long hall that has some very interesting objets d'art from Asia. I would give myself time to read several of the plaques just to enjoy the experience of basically going to a museum on the way to dinner. We were seated very quickly once we arrived. The restaurant has two walls open to the air which views a garden, but it does have what looks like some air conditioning and fans on the interior. I wouldn't go on a hot day.

text:
The restaurant came recommended from a friend we were staying with, and was one of the best places we ate on the island. The portions were very generous, the prices were very reasonable (the same if not cheaper than the mainland), the staff were friendly, and food was great.

It's not exactly fast food, and it's not exactly a sit down restaurant, but somewhere in between. You order in line and wait for a table to become available to sit at, then you bus your own table, and leave. I'd recommend checking it out.

text: Lucy's extremely popular Mexican food restaurant recently updated it's menu and prices, as well as it's sir conditioning system. Easily the best such restaurant in East Hawaii, taqueria plates and vegetarian options in large portions with quick service. Order at the counter then find a seat...or choose the small 3 table and 6 stool bar for awesome house margaritas or tap beer and give your order to the bar tender. You don't have to sit at the bar to drink alcohol but if a seat is open its the best and only way to get table service. Price changes reflect an increase as if September 2019 but it is still a bargain. Children welcome. Small restrooms. Main dining must bus your own table. There is a salsa bar and you can order anything for take-out.

text:
Update 3yrs later on 11-15-2020.  I've been going here weekly since they've opened.
5 stars down to 1 because they messed up my order and refused to fix it.  They gave me half the size burrito I was supposed get.  They still don't have cilantro on the salsa bar.  They're finally a bit more generous with their sour cream though...  They're straight refusal to correct the error in any way citing I didn't bring it to their attention quick enough (1hr) as the reason. This is why my family won't be going there for the next 12 months.  They've missed 48 future meals with my family because of their refusal to take responsibility for their mistake.

text:
Fabulous authentic Mexican food! The fish in my fish tacos was moist, flavorful, flakey, light...absolutely delicious. I asked for a side of avocado and I think it was from a pre-mixed package. (Fyi)
It's a quirky restaurant! There's a sectioned off area where you can drink alcohol...a bar and bartender, and a tv. Then there's a special sectioned off play area in the back of the restaurant for young children. You could sit in the bar while your kid plays in the back of the restaurant!
It's kinda chaotic busy, however, the owner (Lucy's mom) is monitoring the tables so you are guaranteed a seat. She's super sweet and on the ball!!
It's very noisy and a bit warm but you really don't care when you're in there bec Lucy's mom rocks and the food is the bomb!

I had the lengua sopito and it fed me for two entire lunches with the leftovers. The lengua was super tender and the pinto beans are nicely seasoned, not bland at all. Great bartender to boot!

text: I was born and raised in Mexico, I grew up tasting traditional Mexican food, Lucy's Taqueria is one of the best Mexican food restaurants I have ever had the pleasure of dining at!. The frijoles de la hoya are amazing, damn close to the ones abuelita used to make and almost as good as the ones mom still makes, and this is in a clay pot!. The chorizo is as good or better than I remember getting from Tepa, Jalisco. Carne al pastor is suggestive by nature,you will be hard pressed to find a true "Al pastor" taste, however, Lucy's has come up with a very good recipe, one of the best I have tasted. The carnitas are well cooked and taste great. The place is well located and good size. Staff is courteous and attentive, overall,I highly recommend stopping by.....afew times.....as we have......probably having dinner there tomorrow!.

text: If you don't know about this place, you better get there now.  Its a small shop but has what you want.  The staff there is very knowledgeable about the sake.  Though everything is in Japanese,  ask the staff what you like and they know.  So far I haven't had anything that they recommend that I didn't like.  Also you need to be on their email list too.  They bring in limited items in and if you miss it, sorry you missed out BIG time.    And you need to follow them on IG to see the new items.  Also if you ask them nicely, they will hold them for you.   This is the place for all your sake lovers friends and family. And theybhave great gift sets too.
business_description: This snug shop dedicated to sake offers bottles at a range of price points, plus occasional events.

text: Excellent selection. The lady working there was very helpful in picking the right sakes for us and it was really informative and enjoyable. We drank and enjoyed both the sake she suggested to us. Highly recommend

text: Small shop that's tucked in the corner of a small building. They have a decent selection of sake and a small selection of other spirits. I found out about this place because I was helping a friend return a sake barrel that he had rented for his wedding. It seems like their inventory has a little bit of something for all budgets. There were some new stuff that I haven't seen before and ended up buying to give them a try. The person who helped me was very knowledgeable about most of the whiskeys, quick to look up the information on the stuff she didn't know, and had really good recommendations on what to get. I'll definitely go back when I'm ready to get a new bottle of whiskey or sake.
business_description: This snug shop dedicated to sake offers bottles at a range of price points, plus occasional events.

text: My wife and I were walking past this Rolex stores and decided to enter to acquire about purchasing my wife a new Rolex. Upon entering the store we were greeted about one of the store employees named Erin. Her greeting was about as friendly as one would expect entering a graveyard. My wife was curious about a certain watch and was asking Erin if she had any display models she could look at. Erin didn't seem eager to assist my wife. I've seen graveyard robbers more eager to dig up a dead body. She started to ask personal questions such as what kind of Rolex do you own, where did you move from and what do you do for a living. Not only did I take offense to these questions but my wife did as well. She refuses to buy another watch from this store. Erin should be a more friendly to people and not past judgment on to others cause people like me pay for her rent and bills.
business_name: Rolex Boutique Tourneau International Market Place
business_description: Watch shop stocking high-end timepieces from recognizable brands, including some pre-owned.

text: Excellent hike, went during dry conditions. Had some cloud coverage which was great as the most challenging part is completely exposed. There's a lot of strawberry guava trees within the first half mile of the trail. Great place since they control the number of people entering. but the trail is not maintained and the steps up have eroded. They really do need teams to build up boulder steps, replace the dirt steps, or increase vegetation to prevent such erosion. There are ropes to grab to help you along the way. You won't need them if conditions are good but they are in fairly good condition it seemed.

text: This is my new favorite pizza restaurant.  The pizza is huge, nice taste and reasonable price. The sauce is not too heavy, not too sour or salty,  just perfect flavor and the dough was light, crispy at bottom too. The only warning for this place is that inside of the restaurant is like a sauna... so, it's up to you if you wanna eat-in :)

text: Small pizza place with a homey college town restaurant ambience. Love the arcade game and punch strength tester on one corner as well as the eclectic decor rooting for the home team. We always make it a point to visit each time we're in Hawaii. Pizzas are gigantic (don't worry -- you can order per slice) with very delicious and generous toppings. Crust is crunchy, just the way I like it. And you can have your way with the condiments, from crushed oregano and basil to powdered garlic and chili flakes. Tabasco, too (very important). Will definitely come back again and again.

text:
Haven't been to Waikiki in ages, we all got our vaccination, we felt comfortable to get out and enjoy our island paradise!

text: Exceptional waiter and service, large portion sizes with food tasting very good! Dont forget the cheesecake for dessert. So yummy! Got ours to go!
business_description: American chain restaurant offering sizable portions from a vast menu including signature cheesecake

text: Great restaurant in downtown Waikiki. It gets busy, so call ahead to see how long the wait is. If you're driving, park at the Royal Hawaiian Center. Chessecake factory will validate your parking ticket for 3 hours. We decided to try the Sunday brunch menu. The Belgian waffles with strawberries and the Belgian waffles with fried chicken were delicious. It tastes like the strawberries are tossed in sugar and they are delicious. The waffles were fluffy and can be eaten plain or with the side of syrup. Also available is the lunch menu. We tried the BBQ smokehouse burger and the bacan bacon burger. The difference being the thick cut bacon on the bacon bacon burger versus the plain bacon and onion straws on the BBQ burger. Order your burger medium as they usually cook it a little more and anything more than medium results in a well done dry burger.
business_description: American chain restaurant offering sizable portions from a vast menu including signature cheesecake

text: Enjoyed the takeout. Items neatly packaged, quick service although the restaurant was busy. Food was good. With definitely recommend and return for cheesecake, of course!

text: I have never had such great service and food. Our server and the bartender Jenny was friendly and very informative (so awesome). She helped us with what was best to order. The food was very flavorful and delicious. The Southwest egg rolls, steak Taco's were absolutely delicious along with cheesecake that  was of course very tasty. I would absolutely go to the Cheesecake Factory again and make sure to let others know to defiantly try. Not only for the food but for the great staff!

text: Nice restaurant with a very large menu! The AC blows frosty inside with low lighting for that ambience. The Ahi tuna appetizer is the best in my opinion.  Prices are fair, especially for where you are. The cheese cake is epic!  Chocolate mousse and caramel turtle are really good.

anagement has zero control over this restaurant. I have been to several of your restaurant locations and by far this is the worst one when it comes to simple patron flow control. text:
Water took long to come, and our waiter always had us waiting.  Wait long to take our order , food took awhile also.   When we were done eating we wanted to pay but our waiter was no where to be found.  I also noticed two tables next to me were also looking for the waiter.  After having our waiter come to take payment, we went to restroom.   And while leaving the restaurant leaning over the counter to pay for the cheesecake slices facing the workers to we pay for cheesecakes is our waiter playing on her phone.

We were seated outdoor of restaurant in the front , left side of restaurant.  And our server is Caucasian, with blonde hair with a pony tail wearing brown khaki , light brown jeans.
After seeing her playing on the phone , I see why the wait was always long.
I give 1 more star because I see the guy worker who cleans up working his butt off while we wait for our waiter , who plays on her phone.

The area is fairly dim as is most of the restaurant, so we had to view our menus under cell phone lighting, and there is no air conditioning but those small details are easy to overlook by the outstanding service, generous portions and tasty dishes.

This is one of those places in Hawaii that keeps the entire front wall open to the customers and the heat, but tried to run AC in back to have a pleasant temperature in the middle. This never works with the front very hot and the back very cold. On top of that, they tried to save money on the lighting to pay for all that air conditioning. The place was ridiculously dark. So net, I enjoyed the food, but bring your winter coat and miners helmet with headlamp in order to be comfortable at this restaurant.

text:
I know lots of people love it, and the menu is extensive but we struggled to enjoy it.
It started well, the wait was less than advised and we got a great table but that was about it.
The poke ahi was tender but far too much sesame oil was used so it completely overpowered the dish. The salad we ordered from the superfood section was tasty and reasonable portion but the shepherds pie was well below par, it was hard to taste much as the salt was overpowering, no amount of water could dilute the taste of it. We didn't stick around for desert, we tried The Cheesecake Factory but it will be our first and only time, there's so much more on offer in Waikiki. So do yourself a favour, avoid the queue and enjoy the other many food offerings nearby.

text:
I really didn't want to go to this place, but as in all "democratic societies house rules and I was outvoted three to one."  My idea would've been to go across the street to the "International Market Place" and get some inexpensive nourishment like some "sushi and a bowl of ramen."  "Ooh, we did last night, silly me wanting to save some money....

Besides, we had walked the length of the strip and were getting famished.  Of course we didn't make a reservation and like dozens of other people, mostly tourists like ourselves, endured the extended wait.  What I did find amusing was that as we were standing around we all look like a "flock of flamingos," watching and goggling at whoever was attention-grabbing to look at and vise-versa.

I also never detected before, but standing there waiting for our supper, I detected the myriad of different languages spoken from all over the world.  I heard German particularly because I served a tour there and spoke the language.  Waikiki is just a smorgasbord of people from all ethnicities.  Enough about people.

About 45 minutes later, we were called and shuffled into the restaurant and seated at a booth with a view of the interior of shops next to the Cheesecake Factory.  Our waitress arrived promptly and gave us a menu to look at while she retrieved out drink order (that and the bill was the only quick service we got that evening!).

Service was very long in getting around to us, probably due to the enormous volume of tourists like ourselves.  We waited for drinks, refills, and our orders, which took a long time. I ordered the spaghetti just because I love it and wanted to try it for the first time at this place, which as it turned out was a disappointment.  I've unquestionably had better elsewhere and of all the places that we have eaten, one of our favorite restaurants, "Bucca De Peppo" out in California, makes exceptional spaghetti anywhere!

The rest of the table ordered salads to sandwiches and when it came time for the bill it arrived really fast!  The cost of what we ordered also reflected the place, which I thought was a bit expensive.  Now, only if service and the meals could've been just as fast I might have been impressed.

Nothing special about their meals other than in the restaurant's name itself.  In my opinion, this restaurant is more catered to the tourist atmosphere, which brought us to this place for the novelty effect.

text:
We got a table after reserving a table and waiting an hour at before 6:30pm on a Saturday evening when everything was opening back up after the pandemic, which wasn't bad. After we placed our appetizer orders (Fried Calamari and Fried Mac and Cheese balls), our appetizers arrived after 10 minutes. We placed our main course orders and received in another 10 minutes. We had a party of seven, so all of our food came at once, so no one was waiting for their food. I ordered the Shepherd's Pie and for dessert, I got the Caramel Apple Cheesecake.

No one's water was empty for more than a couple of minutes since the wait staff made their rounds pretty diligently, and soft drinks were refilled pretty quickly once they were notified of it.

From my party, no one had any complaints of their food, and some of us were so stuffed that we brought home a couple bags of unfinished food in to-go containers. We had to transfer our own food dishes from the plates to the containers - I don't know if that's how they did it prior to this pandemic, or it was the way because of it.

I don't usually go out to eat at a restaurant like this, and I don't know where it stands on how fancy it is, but what I do know is that I'll be coming back when I'm either in the neighborhood (Waikiki is a far drive from my home) or will come back when we are celebrating another social event.

text: Waikiki Beach is an absolutely great beach for everyone. I consider Waikiki beach the ambassador beach. It has all you need for a great day at the beach. The sand is nice and very fine. The water has the ability to kick up some small surf but has always been an ideal for kids or new swimmers. Life guards are in every direction. Along the street (strip) there are tons of great attractions and amenities (free public restrooms, outstanding eateries, and plenty of activities to make your outing as safe and as memorable as possible. This is one of the most popular beaches on the strip. The amount of people that accumulate at one time is the one and only reason Waikiki beach isn't considered "perfect".

text: What else can I say but still one of the best beaches in the world!! I grew up on this beach from bodyboarding at walls as a child; to surfing at publics, kaiser's, and bowls as a teen; to longboarding at queens, canoes, and pops as an adult. I worked on this beach as a beachboy in my youth and now I enjoy bringing my kids to this beach to share all that I have learned with them. This beach has everything that you could ever want want right at its fingertips.. from bodyboarding to surfing to longboarding to snorkeling to diving to swimming to floating to just laying out in the sun. And when you get hungry or thirsty, there's a hundred places to choose from right there. There's literally something for everyone here at Waikiki beach.

text: This is another stunning state park in Hawaii, where you would fall in love with the nature at its best. There is stunning waterfall, inside the green tropical forest. There is a small paved hiking trail ( more precisely bridges) to reach the actual lookout point. However, if you do not want to hike, you can stay outside, because the falls is still visible from there. But I would definitely recommend the hiking through the humid, green nature. This would give you some different experience of a rain forest with its typical smell and sound. The waterfall looks really nice. The parking lot is small and gated. They close the gate by 5:30 pm. So if you are late, park outside ( as we did without any problem).

text:
We were hoping to have a picnic lunch here and hike out to the waterfall.  You pay to park your car in the parking lot and there are a couple picnic tables near the parking lot.

We ate lunch at one of the picnic tables and then went down to do the "hike".  It's basically a small circle loop that is a fenced in path to the waterfall and back.  Half of the circle loop was closed because it looked like a large palm tree had fallen on it.  The portion of the circle loop we did was shaded and you pass some other pretty waterfalls on the way to the main falls.

The waterfall is beautiful and I am glad we came to saw it.  Although the "hike" there and back took maybe 10 to 15 minutes.  It was a pretty quick stop for the long drive out.  I would recommend planning your day with some other waterfall stops to make the drive worth it.

Make sure to hit the bakery in the small town outside of the falls!  They have some amazing preserves and breads!

text:
An amazing true Korean BBQ buffet experience right in Honolulu. It's truly all you can eat. You simply go up to the buffet and grab your meat and sides and cook at your table. They also have a selection of sushi, sashimi, soups and tempura.

Be careful to only take from the buffet what you will actually eat. Leaving a lot of leftovers will incur an extra fee. The staff was very kind and attentive, however some of their English isn't perfect, so please be patient. I would definitely suggest trying this place out!
business_description: Informal buffet offering all-you-can-eat Korean cuisine for guests to cook at in-table grills.

text: Got there at Dinner time and was fairly busy, but got seated after about a 5 minute wait.  Had severs at the buffet line, but it went smoothly   First time dining in a restaurant in over a year.  They did contact tracing by asking to fill out a form with name, address, and phone information.
business_description: Informal buffet offering all-you-can-eat Korean cuisine for guests to cook at in-table grills.

text: In the times I've eaten here, I've always enjoyed myself, between being able to eat ahi poke all you can eat and grilling the various meats offered. I would stick to mainly those two areas, since the other options are more standard fare, and I didn't feel like they sacrificed the quality of their food despite it being a buffet. Great place to splurge a bit.
business_description: Informal buffet offering all-you-can-eat Korean cuisine for guests to cook at in-table grills.

text: Dinner price is higher than most yakiniku places, but having ayce sashimi and sushi was definitely a game changer. Definitely recommend to anyone who's looking for a good ayce restaurant.

text: Ahi and Vegetables' newest venture is a hit.   Some may lament the passing of the old Camilla Buffet, but McCully Buffet surpasses the former.   Better select, fresher ingredients and new yakiniku cookers make dining a pleasure.  Try 'em!

text: Best Korean Bar B Q on the island.   And the owner is easy on the eyes.  She even honored my dads coupons.  Great food.  I ate my own body weight in meat and veggies. Had to change out the table grill like 4 times.  Dad loved it too.  Will definitely eat here again, whenever I come back to the island.  Love this place.
business_description: Informal buffet offering all-you-can-eat Korean cuisine for guests to cook at in-table grills.

text: I have eaten at Camellia Buffet many times over the years and it has been consistently excellent. Korean BBQ buffets always have a wide variety of meats. Camellia has the largest and best variety I have encountered. The following photographs will illustrate that. There is also a large variety of other food selections. text:

FOOD: The food was really good, not dry and no "oldness" when we went. My favorite was the CHICKEN which paired really well with the yakiniku sauce right after it comes off the grill. My wife really liked the PORK BELLY. I also enjoyed the FRIED RICE which is just right, its not oily like before.

REQUEST: Please bring back the Jello!!

SERVICE: Though I miss some of the old workers who were really nice the new workers are very nice, always checking on us to see if everything is alright and if we needed anything to constantly refilling our waters and sodas to changing out our grill several times during the course of the meal. But most importantly there was no attitude when you ask them for something.

PARKING: Decent size lot with 2 handicap parking spaces. Did not have difficulty finding a parking spot during lunch time on a Saturday even with several families already dining.

WILL DEFINITELY BE BACK NOW!!

text: This is the first time I've tried this place. The restaurant was clean, hip, and the staff was very friendly. I ordered the garlic miso ramen, and it was quite good. The noodles were not soggy. I really liked the texture. It came with 2 pieces of Cha siu. I think they were ok. They had a good proportion of fat and meat, but it was a bit tough. The soup was good. I liked how they added sesame, onions and bamboo shoots. But honestly, I couldn't taste the garlic flavor too much. The one great surprise was the chicken karaage. The chickens were fleshly fried, and the meat was still very juicy. It also came with Himalayan salt. This dish worked really well. I highly recommend it. In general I enjoyed the experience here, and would definitely come back again.

text: Food is good, consistent with other locations.  However, it's primarily the staffing here that is the issue (particularly the older workers).  During busy times, the older employees here become very flustered and lose all sense of customer service.  They no longer smile or give you proper answers when you have questions.  I asked one of them if there are free refills when I dine in.  She responded with, "you get 1 refill".  I went to get a refill later and another lady angrily told me "no refills.  You have to pay".  She eventually refilled my drink after I gave some lip back.

text: Ordered wafu steak today. The meat was tender (no need a knife) and tasty. Oroshi daikon was really matching with the steak. Garlic chips added some flavor, but not overwhelmed. Overall this is the most authentic Japanese meal that I have ever had in Oahu!

text:
If you are in the mood for some great Indian curry in a hurry and in the downtown Honolulu area, you have got to check this place out.  The food is just amazing.  So fresh and full of flavors.

Don't worry if you are not a fan of hot food, they do have mild curries to choose from.  Also, being Indian food, there are lots of vegetarian options for those living on a plant based diet.

For me, it has got to have meat and be spicy.  I zeroed in on the Pepper Chicken and Lamb Tikka Masala. Wow, both were over the top with great spices and preparation.  The yellow rice was a nice compliment for the curries, but if you want brown rice, they got that as well.

They have a few other items other then curry to complete or make your meal and I really enjoyed my homemade Ginger Lemonade that I got to wash down the spice with. Really was perfect to cleanse the palate after such a flavor extravaganza.

If you need to get your Indian curry fix on, I really recommend this place.
business_description: Health-minded weekday lunch spot serving Indian cuisine, including vegetarian options.

text:
I was a bit hesitant to write this review, but here it goes.

RATS!   Rats!  rats!

Running wild!  in the Storage Area of the kitchen where are the plates, silverware, cups and cooking pans are kept.

Personally I was a huge fan of Treetops Restaurant and LOVE the location.

But after "The New Management" took over this year, its clear to see they have it all wrong.

RATS!

From the 7 balconies, Especially in the Storage Area behind the kitchen where are the plates, silverware, cups and cooking pans are kept.

They do not have a front door to the restaurant, just a roll up gate.  (They were advised to put a door and screens on to enclose the entire restaurant, but they did not listen).

This means rats, bugs, birds and anything that can fit can stroll on in.

Sounds harsh I know, but I have seen them with My Own Eyes on many occasions.

You can see the traces of them... small brown droppings.

And have taken pictures of them.... Gray Hair small eyes.

Think of it, the restaurant is in the Rain Forest, with no door and missing screen on the windows....

I hate to mention all that.

Some pleasant servers who care about their jobs, but the food and environment is lacking quality control.

I am contacting the Health Inspector so they will hopefully clean up their act.

Too bad, I love the location, but not the infestation of Rats!

text: Who doesn't like Chinese fast food?!?!  I know I do.  Panda Express has been around for years. When I'm busy and need to get tasty food fast, I head down to Panda Express. Most times the dishes are full of food and ready to put on my plate. There is a joke we have here in Hawaii, we use the term Pake aka Chinese meaning tight. This location sticks to whatever food the fits in that small scooper. Can ya just give me a little more?  If they did, I would give 5 stars.
business_description: Fast-food chain for Chinese standards, including some health-conscious options.

text: Management is a joke called them about a issue on my plate I bought for lunch spoke to Amy and she asked if I still have my plate. I told her no I lost my appetite at that time so I threw away the plate. So she said she would fix my order witch I was fine with. When I went back to the store spoke with her she informed me the reason witch I understand but what came next was really messed up I paid for a 3 choice plate she was going only give me a 2 choice explained to her how is that when I paid for a 3 choice and she was going give me a 2 choice as a replacement then she said this time I'll do the 3 choice. So that means if they mess up they can short us from what we paid never experienced that from any pandas before. While she was redoing my order I had to wait on the side and she made the plate. When given she gave me someone else's plate??!! I'm confused how that happened I was done with the irresponsibility from them I wanted to leave. I'm never going to that location again. Just another note I didn't put what the issue was so let you guys imagine the problem
business_description: Fast-food chain for Chinese standards, including some health-conscious options.

text: This is a great hike for hikers of all experience levels.  There is plenty of parking along the residential street at the trailhead, just be sure to be respectful of the property and driveways.  The gate will be shut and labeled with no trespassing signs.  Feel free to walk right around it on the well-worn trail where hundreds of other people have done it.  The first half of the trail is a gravel road, with very little incline. Eventually, it turns to a dirt trail that gets a good bit steeper on and off until you reach the waterfall.  Even if there's been no recent rain, this is one of the more beautiful falls on the island.  There's also a nice swimming hole about halfway down the trail.  There should be an obvious path to follow, and it's about 15-20 yds off of the main trail.  It can be a little muddy at times, but you can make it in almost any foot gear if you're careful.
business_description: A rocky cascade in a forested valley, accessed via a hiking trail with a swimming hole on the way

text:
For me, OVERRATED restaurant!!! My husband cooks a way better steak and seafood dinner!!!!

Out of fairness to the negative tone of my review - I think providing a little more detail on my personal experience on this occasion would be fair to the restaurant.

I attended this restaurant with a group of 17 ladies.  We were seated at 2 tables next to each other with 10 ladies on one table and 7 ladies on another.

The waiter came around and took all our orders.  As the food came to the table,  there was a slight confusion on the orders.  Two people at our table got the wrong order. But instead of returning the order - they opted to eat what was in front of them to avoid waiting for their correct order to come out.

Honestly,  the original waiter returned to our table ONCE after everyone got their food.  We requested refills on water and drinks - no one came to refill our table.

The food wasn't anything different than what's served at any steakhouse.  It wasn't an experience that deserved 5 stars for the amount of monies we spent for this gathering.  I definitely voted that our group never return there. Not for the monies we paid and the lack of service we received along with the food being just "okay."
business_description: Outpost of upmarket steakhouse chain known for sizzling, butter-topped beef in an elegant setting

text: My wife and I had been wanting to eat at this highly recommended steakhouse since moving to Hawaii and finally got the chance last night. Ample parking, elevator access and great views from the second-floor lanai. Hostess was quick to accommodate our request to sit outside - they hadn't planned on opening the lanai last night but she said no problem and we were seated at a table within 5 minutes. Service staff was excellent and helped us choose the right dishes in consideration of my wife's dairy allergy. Menu was not large but there were plenty of protein options to satisfy any appetite. Portions were larger than expected - everything was a-la-carte and we badly miscalculated, each of us ordering a steak and 2 sides, leaving us with plenty of leftovers to bring home. Service included complimentary bread and butter, as well as champagne and dessert on the house (we were celebrating our 12th wedding anniversary). Prices were high but certainly comparable to other premium steak houses we've visited, all with unsurpassed service. If you're hungry for a delicious steak and looking for a novel dining experience, don't miss Ruth's Chris Steak House in Mauna Lani. There is full wheelchair access to this restaurant, though I never checked out the washroom during our visit.
business_description: Outpost of upmarket steakhouse chain known for sizzling, butter-topped beef in an elegant setting

text: Ordered my Green Ice Tea on my mobile. Got to the store saw about 3 customers waiting for their order.  4 employees working, 1 at cashier, 2 making drinks, 1 went in the back store room. At this time, 3 other customers came in ordered their drinks with the cashier and received them before I got mine. How is that possible??? My drink was just a Green ice tea. The darn tea is already made. After 15 mins, I was literally the 2nd to the last person to leave the store...I was going to say something but knew it would just be a Sorry thing and not be sincere. This is not my 1st encounter at the Moanalua store. Don't think I will be going there anymore.  This was a last minute decision to go there in my way home. Bad mistake!!!

text:
Delicious Middle Eastern flavors. Chef Michael Mina has done well adapting this palette to the island. Chicken lafa was juicy and flavorful, and the veggies tasted extra fresh! Zaatar fries were a fantastic side dish, with the cheese complimenting the zaatar.

On a second visit had the beef and a side of falafel. Probably even more delicious than the chicken!

Third: have now had the salmon, which flakes and then melts in your mouth, but also really highlights the taste of the vegetables.
business_description: Creative Mediterranean ingredients combinations are folded into wraps at this food-court stand.

text: For fast casual this food is exceptional. Get the veggie lafa...roasted cauliflower and eggplant with chickpeas, harissa, Zaatar and halloumi.

text:
This place is an awesome little gem in Old Wailuku town. Eating under the banyan tree is a great experience.

They have a good variety of standard fare on the menu as well as daily specials which sometimes includes fresh fish.

The curries are great, pad Thai and drunken noodle also cooked to perfection. I also like the chicken ginger stir fry and fried rice.  Oh, and the service...super friendly and accommodating.

You gotta check this place out when you need your next Thai food fix.

text:
UPDATED REVIEW: I originally gave Artizen 2 stars.  I added another star because my food arrived cooked this time.  If ordering online, the menu is limited.  You have to go in for the full menu.  Still on the slow side.  Food is good, not great.

OLD REVIEW:  I heard great things, but my first experience was not good by any means (raw hamburger and not ready on time).  I can see it being good, though. I ordered online for a pick up at 11:30 (paid online, too). Came in on time, asked about my order, and was told it'll be a second. I waited ten minutes and asked again. It turned out they didn't start my order until I after arrived.  I got my food almost 20 minutes after it was supposed to be ready. When I got back to the office, I found the burger was RED AND COLD on the inside.  I asked for medium, this was not close to that. It also looked like it was thrown in there with no attempt to construct a burger, maybe I was meant to build it myself.  It all seemed rushed, which is a shame given the quality of the good looked good.

I did not feel like going back to fix it or get a refund.

The fries were fine, but definitely over salted.

Maybe I went on an off day, but it was bad.

I'll go again because their other restaurant is great and the menu here looks promising.  I'll revise my rating if the experience improves.

text:
This place is a hidden gem in Honolulu. The less expensive and more accessible offshoot of its parent restaurant, Artizen is a great choice for fresh, inventive, upscale cuisine in quick serve format.

The menu is extensive and offers a variety of fusion dishes from poke to burgers to bento boxes.

The poke was delicately flavored with sweet white onions and a delicious chili oil, and was serve with a bowl of perfectly cooked and aggressively seasoned rice. Short ribs are rich and tender, and the soy based sauce combines with the rice for a complete experience.

Patrons are primarily workers from around the offices surrounding the art gallery the eatery is located in... This place is legit and not a tourist trap

I would recommend lunch here if you're in the area visiting Iolani Palace.

text: This Starbucks is super convenient if you're staying at the Westin. It has a full-service Starbucks menu with drinks and breakfast options. The hours are very limited though (they close at 11am), and you can't order on the Starbucks mobile app so give yourself an extra 20-30 minutes in case the line gets long (which it does). There's also a Starbucks 5 minutes down the road in Lahaina and it does take mobile orders so if you're venturing out around the island, choose this option and mobile order when you leave the hotel - it will be ready for pick-up by the time you arrive. (The drive-thru at that off-campus Starbucks is always terrible so make sure to mobile order and walk in.)

text:
The churchyard at Waiola Church is the final resting place for most of the Hawaiian Royal Family and is widely recognized as Maui's first church. Queen Keopuolani was baptized at Waiola on September 16, 1823.

I have been attending Waiola whenever I'm on island since the early nineties. Although I live 2600 miles away and seldom visit more than once a year, Waiola has always made me feel like ohana (family). Aside from its rich heritage and historical importance to Maui, Waiola Church is an integral part of Lahaina's present -- providing both spiritual guidance and cultural insight to all who visit.
business_description: Site of the first Christian mission on Maui, known for Hawaiian royalty buried in its cemetery.

text: This was my second visit to Casablanca. Both times, my friends and I got the prix fixed menu. All dishes are consistently well made and very tasty, and the presentation is beautiful. Use of utensils is optional, and eating without utensils is a fun experience. The meal starts with everyone washing their hands at the table with warm water that is poured by the server. The meal ends with dessert that is served with sweet mint tea, a Moroccan staple. The dining area is comfortable and relaxed with beautiful Moroccan furniture and rugs. The staff are welcoming, accommodating and attentive. Casablanca is great place to enjoy a delicious meal with friends and family. A true gem on the windward side. There are only a few parking spots in front of the restaurant but there is street parking available.
business_description: Elegant BYO restaurant for traditional Moroccan cuisine served in fixed-price 5-course meals.

First course is the lentil soup, Harrira and that is provided in a bowl per person. Second is the Morrocan salad severed with bread. Third is b'stilla and this filo pastry appetizer can be ordered with chicken or ordered vegetarian. Fourth course is the entree, and people order their own dishes off the menu. Finally, dessert is funnel cakes with chocolate almonds and biscotti. The mint tea is a nice end to this meal, helping to digest the food that was enjoyed.

text:
I love this place.  Man.... I used to eat at this place when they were across Windward Mall.  And then they closed down and I never knew what happened to them.  All these years... maybe like 10 years or something, I never know they were in Temple Valley until my dad wanted to meet there for breakfast.

I ordered their fried rice and a side of potato salad, both my favorites from before.  The fried rice was delicious.  The potato salad wasn't as great as I remembered it.  Think I needed to just add a little more salt and it would have been perfect, but my son and husband liked it so it's still a winner in my book.

Would definitely come back here if I was in the area for breakfast!

text: Nice little Cantonese Chinese restaurant in the Salt Lake Shopping center. Conveniently located next to Safeway and Shaka Shaka Tea several other eateries like McDonald's.  Food is good, prices are fair and portions are decent. Been going here a while and occasionally that change in cooks makes the food inconsistent but generally they are our standby Chinese food spot.  Favorites are salted fish fried rice, mapo tofu, eggplant with minced pork, garlic chicken over cake noodle, black bean clams, salt and pepper dished (port chops, chicken or squid all tasty).  Staff has been really friendly and helpful but speaking Chinese probably helps the cause but our friends who don't speak still get good service.  Ever since portions got really small and Wah Kung in the old 99 ranch complex changed ownership, we have been coming here.  You should stop if you are into traditional Cantonese fare.
business_description: A broad menu of Chinese dishes from different regions served in a relaxed, shopping-center locale.

text: Had the rare opportunity to visit and see the newly completed renovations. Also met the governor and his wife.
business_description: Built in 1847, this mansion has been the home of Hawaii's rulers, starting with Queen Lili'uokalani.

text: This is a beautiful structure, and one that in many ways represents the colonial past that Hawaii has wrestled with. If you don't have time for a tour, you can get great pictures from the street. I would encourage making a reservation and going through the house. It's story is important to this once colony, now state.
business_description: Built in 1847, this mansion has been the home of Hawaii's rulers, starting with Queen Lili'uokalani.

text: The Docent that took us on the tour was very knowledgeable.  The history of Washington Place is good for all of us that live in Hawaii should know.  My Kupuna group from Kapolei enjoyed it. Some of the group has never been there and appreciated it. Good tour!!
business_description: Built in 1847, this mansion has been the home of Hawaii's rulers, starting with Queen Lili'uokalani.

text:
This place is something most people don't think of as a historical place to visit.  It is an important part of Hawaii's history leading up to modern times, but it wasn't until recent years did become open to the public for free tours every Thursday.

The tour space is very limited, so it is a good idea to plan in advance.  You can easily book online to confirm available space.  Again, it is free, so this is a no lose deal.  The docents take you back in time to really help you understand everything about the property and events that have happened over time.

Being located next to the State Capital, Iolani Palace, and State Art Museum, you can make a day of it just touring Hawaii's history in one walkable area.

I don't recommend this for young children as it will be boring for them and they will disturb others who are trying to listen to the docent.  This is a very adult and mentally mature type of activity.
business_description: Built in 1847, this mansion has been the home of Hawaii's rulers, starting with Queen Lili'uokalani.

text:
Located in a prime spot across the ocean and overlooking the aqua farm, this restaurant is a nice spot for a different than town eatery.
They offer a full bar, medium entree options, sushi and a variety of seafood specials.
Personally love their Kumamoto oysters and tried the lava cake for dessert.
Make a reservation and go early  enough to catch the scenic view and good parking.
business_name: The Seaside Restaurant and Aqua Farm
business_description: Family-owned spot for Hawaiian-style surf 'n' turf featuring fresh catches from on-site aqua farm.

text: Nice sit down restaurant for a meal on the fancier side. The Chinese steamed fish was very flavorful, and I especially enjoyed the ahi poke nachos! They're served on fried wonton skins with a very light sweet and sour sauce.

business_description: Family-owned spot for Hawaiian-style surf 'n' turf featuring fresh catches from on-site aqua farm.

text: I've been here only twice but the second time I went I had such a nice and friendly waitress. I think her name was Ka'iu but I'm not too sure. You can really tell she cares about her job a lot and takes it very seriously. She studied the specials of the day by memory even down to what kind of ingredients that were in the sauces they had and recommended some dishes. Every time I leave this restaurant I remember how great the service was and I'll always remember that about this restaurant.

text:
We went for dinner on a week night.  We didn't have reservations.  We were seated quickly. Our waitress came to the table and before she could tell us the specials - we were ready to order what was on the menu.  I enjoyed appetizers and my husband had a steak that he really enjoyed.

We were too full to eat desserts but in the past - we both enjoyed their mud pie. Something different was the live music being played by a solo guitarist.  It created a peaceful ambience but just the company and the quietness was all I needed for the evening.  The food was the icing on the cake!
business_name: The Seaside Restaurant and Aqua Farm
business_description: Family-owned spot for Hawaiian-style surf 'n' turf featuring fresh catches from on-site aqua farm.

text: My husband and I usually love going here, but this time we left unsatisfied. I ordered the rib eye med rare and it came to me bloody and still mooing. I had it sent back because I don't like my steaks to be rare. When my food returned, I was surprised to see that it was the same steak I had cut into. They didn't even make me a new steak. I felt like that was unsanitary to put a customer's food back into a pan and continue cooking. Even though they put it back on the heat, the steak was still rare and I was unable to eat it. Luckily our waiter was wonderful and I did not pay for my rib eye. This place is nice and one of my favorite restaurants in Hilo, but please, if you like your steak cooked, don't order the rib eye.

text: We stopped at The Seaside because we happened to be in the area. I'm glad we did. The cute back room overlooked the tide pool where some fish are raised, and being fairly early, we had our choice of seats. While I was expecting to order local seafood choices, we had to defer when King crab was on the menu. It was cooked perfectly and made is scoff at the Maine lobster we are more used to. The volcano shrimp was nice, and if not for splurging on the crab (we split each order) would have been a favorite. Our server was very friendly and she gave us several recommendations of things to do on the big island including crossing the street to look for turtles on the beach.

text:
If you are tired of Pho, you have to try King of Thai Boat Noodles for that noodle soup experience at a whole different level.

Don't get me wrong, I still love pho noodles, but it is kind of the same after a while. Thai boat noodles offer richer soup bases and more varieties of noodle choices to change it up from the simplicity of pho noodle soups.

The Combination Beef Noodle Soup offers a rich and spicy dark broth loaded with hearty chunks of different beef. It is truly filling and satisfying, so you won't be hungry for a while.

For something way different, there is the Yen Ta Fo Noodle Soup. It offers lots of seafood in a red bean based broth that is impossible to describe, but something you must try. I am not sure if it is for everyone and probably need to be in the mood for it, but very good all the same.

The Crab Meat Fried Rice is a great dish to share. It has lots of crab meat that has been perfectly fried with onions in the rice. Simple on the ingredients, which is perfect for highlighting the crab meat flavor that comes out.

Of course they make classic Thai Green Papaya Salad, which is made fresh to order. The balance of ingredients really makes this dish a perfect starter or side with you order.

The place is very clean and well lighted. Service was friendly and fast. Over all value of their dish prices was very good and well worth it.  This review was written after my second visit and I plan to go again for sure, so yes, I do recommend trying it.
business_description: Thai specialties dished up in a down-to-earth, intimate noodle house with purple decor.

text: Such food!  Very wow!
business_description: Thai specialties dished up in a down-to-earth, intimate noodle house with purple decor.

text: I am Thai and I am happy to say King of Thai Boat Noodles serves up authentic Thai food. From the delicious warm chewy flaky roti and curry dip appetizer to the variety of noodle dishes, you will get authentic non westernized Thai flavors. Ask what the weekend specials are, you won't be disappointed and will get the real deal . Several unique menu items. We had khanom jeen on a Sunday, (somen noodles w spicy aromatic curry n veggies) and pig's feet stew on Saturday. Delicious! Plenty of parking on the street or at Wal-Mart or Ross.
business_description: Thai specialties dished up in a down-to-earth, intimate noodle house with purple decor.

text:
For the beginner: The room themes were clever. I'd recommend the Y2K style room. Bring a group and have fun. Not a bad place to start to get into escape rooms if you're just looking to have a little fun.

The for experienced: I've done all of their rooms now and would only recommend one of them to a friend (Y2K). The other rooms had broken or missing clues. We tried to challenge a couple we know but when we did the same room an entire set of clues was left out. If you're bored and really need a scratch your escape room itch give it a go. If you can wait, if definitely wait.

Plus side: they let you book private rooms for a small fee for each person. Not bad when you want to do it with only two people for the challenge. Other places make you rent out the entire room.

text:
If you're thirsty at Hukilau Marketplace, So'Da Bomb is the way to go! They have a bunch of different soda mix options and they've got something for everyone! They have mix-ins with Dr Pepper, Ginger Ale, Lemonade, Mountain Dew, Mist Twist, Orange, Pepsi, Root Beer.

Our go to is the Honey Mooner which is a mix of Mountain Dew, red raspberry, strawberry and peach. It's so good!

The prices are decent for the sizes and not too bad. Make sure you get the punch card so if you like it enough, you can get a free drink after purchasing 10 drinks.

text:
For mall food the Ramen and Gyoza was ok!  I ordered the Miso Ramen and its a good thing that I dont mind bean sprouts because that is pretty much all it was.  Dont get me wrong there was noodles, and two pieces of pork but the bean sprouts overpowered everything but the broth.
Before dining here I read reviews of the staff being friendly.  Not sure if we came on a bad day but our server seemed like she did not want to be there, no smile, no warm welcome, all we got was "You ready to order?" and when she brought our food, she just placed it on the table, walked away and did not come back to check on us once, only to bring usbour bill when she saw we were finished.
I might give it one more try, cause like i said, not sure if we came on a bad day.

text:
I placed an order online and was told that there was a 15-minute wait for carry out.  When I arrived at the store, the sole employee was telling customers that he was the only person working that day, and that he had not yet started to make pizzas for customers who had already been waiting over 45 minutes.  Finally, nearly 80 minutes after I placed the order, it was ready.

What really bothered me about this experience, though, was the fact that as new customers came into the store to place an order, they were told that their pizza would be ready in 15 minutes, when the employee clearly knew this to be false--one of these customers had been there an hour when I left. I can handle waiting for a pizza--backups happen and staff shortages can be unexpected. But I think it's disgraceful for a restaurant to actually lie to their customers and falsely elevate a guest's expectations so that the guest doesn't go elsewhere.

text: An absolute MUST when you're in Maui. My wife introduced me during one of my first trips to Hawaii and I've been in love ever since. Conveniently located in Downtown Lahaina, it's great to grab and walk around. Don't forget all of the fixings!

text:
Pick your size, add 3 flavors of syrup.
You can also add free extras like Kauai cream, mochi balls, and ice cream all for free.

Chill shave ice with service not in a hurry. If the lines out the door just walk down the street to one of the other places using the same machines and syrups.

I suspect that the abundance of great ratings has more to do with the proximity to the tree than being better than other shops in the area.

text: This is a hidden gem. It might appear another usual eatery from the outside, you will understand their class once you eat. The nice laid back and informal environment is perfect as a place for hanging out with friends. It was pretty crowded when we visited. You have to stand in a long queue and order, choosing from the crust to toppings. Their ingredients are so fresh and good in quality. They will prepare everything from scratch, including the dough. Then would bake it in the stone oven. All the pizzas were very nice and fresh. I would definitely recommend the place to others.

text:
This place is in the Koko Marina shopping center so there's plenty of parking usually. They have made to order pizza, salads, bread knots and I believe chicken wings.

I always go for their made to order pizza. I usually go for three toppings. They have a wide variety of both meat and vegetable toppings along with several types of cheese...to include ricotta which I love.

To top it off this is a locally owned place. The owner is really nice and he always seems to have the placed staffed with a couple great workers. What's not to love about that? Support your local businesses!

text:
3.5 Stars if I could. Definitely not a 4 star.
Pretty limited with crust options. No thin, pan crust or cauliflower.
They don't allow unlimited toppings per pizza, and charge extra over 3 choices.

They do however offer some local flair. Unfortunately it doesn't work too well. I've had their Bulgogi, and Kalua pig pizzas. Meh.

The best part of their offerings is a half pizza. My daughter is able eat a half pizza with a salad. That works out as a meal for her

text: It doesn't look like much from the outside, but the inside is nice, and the food is fantastic. The pizza is freshly made with a great tasting mozzarella and red sauxe that has that slight Tang you always look for in a good sauce. If you aren't a fan of red sauce or mozzarella, they offer 6 total choices of cheese, and 4 sauces, as well as over 20 something toppings. The pizza are good enough I had to order seconds. Staff is extremely friendly. Highly worth the trip, and is worthy of it's nearly 5 star reviews

text:
Just discovered this pizzaria! It's a fun place to eat, with amazing toppings You can make your own pizza with an "ingredients"  bar rivaling Subway and Ruby Tuesday. Sauces, pizza doughs, and toppings are made fresh daily.
We had the Sophie's original crust with the macadamia cream sauce and a wonderful variety of toppings from the usual pepperoni, black olives, mushrooms, and onions to pineapple and Kimchee.
If you want something different and awesome, this is the place to go!

text: Visited Pai Honolulu for Restaurant Week (RW). Its located inside the Harbor Court building on Nimitz Blvd. It's on the smaller size of restaurants but simply inviting. Aesthetics very clean, modern and borderline industrial. We were seated at the bar side and the place holders were locally sourced so that in itself is a plus. We were offered the restaurant week menu as well as the house menu. We opted for restaurant week and glad for it. The RW menu included two options for each course, a 3-course menu (see picture). The pictures say it all and likely does not do it justice. Each dish was well thought out, paired well with wine options and delectable but very filling.  My favorite was the NZ green-lipped mussel as well as the chocolate brownie. Well done, Pai Honolulu! We will need to come again to try your regular menu!

text:
If the inspectors of a certain tire company were to pass through Honolulu, PAI would be worth a stop. I stopped by for the Chef's Seasonal Tasting Menu, which was more of an experience than the mere consumption of quality sustenance.

Course after course of thoughtful and varied fare that wasn't overly complicated. A standout for me was the Agedashi Tofu, which had a little bit of smoked fish on top and was remarkable. The cocktails are a good choice, and I'd suggest you try kind of a omakase with their bartender. I had some drinks which were on par with the excellent food, capped off by this inventive tea cocktail which I enjoyed greatly.

The whole place is clean, impressively so. The staff are professional and highly attentive, while remaining unobtrusive. The tasting menu was a good choice, because there's so much good food that you could become paralyzed with indecision.

Planning on returning.
business_description: Sophisticated restaurant featuring refined, internationally-inspired fare, with tasting menus.

text: We came here for my husbands 40 birthday and while expensive, I feel like it was worth every penny!  We had a counter seating which allowed us to watch over the food preparation and talk to the staff (which resulted in getting 2 extra deserts for free).  We ordered the chefs tasting menu. My husband had the caviar as an add-on.  Honestly I would not recommend getting the caviar - we assumed that that would mean he'd get an extra dish with caviar but instead he got it just added on top of 3 dishes, which honestly was a bit overpowering and detracted from those dishes.  Everything else was great.  All in all,if definitely recommend it for a big celebration!

text:
I really enjoyed touring this shop and purchasing a glass wave.  The staff inside were very friendly and I arranged easily for shipping back to my home without my having to be responsible for it in my bags.  It was both heavy and delicate so shipping was well worth the additional cost.

There are many beautiful glass pieces in here for decor and also some functional ones light sconces and bar lighting.

I like that the workshop is active and you can see live demonstrations of how they make the glass.

It's very beautiful and some of the best craftsmanship I saw.  I also so their items at the Four Seasons hotel at Wailea where I stayed where they were featured one day in the open air space and at the ferry landing the day I arrived in a few of the art galleries.

This shop is located in a charming town with tons of other nearby shops to visit and small restaurants so you can easily make an afternoon out of looking around.

text:
This italian restaurant was a great experience.
The food was much better than expected, and the decor was very nice.
For the food...
The table bread was warm and delicious, light crust and fluffy inside.
I ordered the sausage and meatball with rigatoni; The red sauce was outstanding, the pasta was perfect, and the meatball was alright, but the sausage left me a little disappointed. I never seem to like restaurant meatballs, no one will ever live up to my Nana's cooking so I'll let that slide. Also I'm not a fan of sweet sausage as it is, but it was just bleh for me either way.
The grated cheese added a lot to the flavor of my meal, I'd suggest having them heap it on.

As for the restaurant itself...
The telephone at the front door was constantly ringing at a high volume for the duration of my visit. I understand that they need to take orders and reservations over the phone, but it doesn't need to be on high volume when someone should be there watching the door anyway.
My servers however, were very cheerful and attentive. It definitely improved my experience.

I'd definitely visit this place again when I'm looking for moderately priced Italian in a higher class atmosphere.

text: Gyotaku is a local chain of Japanese restaurants that serves family-style food, more or less, plus plenty of sushi options. As such, it's more expensive than a noodle shop, but cheaper than a sushi shop. The maybe (one pot) dishes and donburi (rice bowl) dishes are popular, and I particularly like the bento dishes. They take limited reservations, so most seating is first-time, first-seated. I ate lunch at the Aina Hai Na location, and the crowd was mostly older folks, and the service was good. There's a "kids eat free" special on Mondays and Tuesdays.
business_description: Family-friendly establishment serving an extensive menu of local-style Japanese fare.

text: Our family of 4 went hoping to love this bakery based on reviews, but we were all disappointed.  For those that love a good crunchy cookie that is completely baked and crunchy throughout with no softness at all, this place is for you. But if you love softer (slightly underbaked) chewy cookies like we do, you will be disappointed. They tasted fine, but just way too crunchy for our preference. I would honestly characterize them as somewhat overbaked.  We'll be trying out some other bakeries on this trip and will update this review as we work our way around the big island.

It's a fun hike. Pretty muddy. I'd advise not going if it's raining. Once you hike down to by the water, there are a couple places where you can swim. There's a water fall you can jump from, but before you do, be aware of where the hidden rocks are below. There's also a rope swing, but, once again, there's a large rock almost directly under the swing. Jump with care.

text: Beautiful 2 mile hike through the trees to two sets of waterfalls. Trail is damp and muddy so be prepared. Rope swing at the end of the second waterfall if you want to jump in and swim.
business_description: A hiking trail through a jungle leads to this series of scenic waterfalls with pools for swimming.

text: What an amazing place! My wife, Dad and I hiked here on July 5th-without searching online for directions you pretty much won't be able to find it. A shorter jungle hike(1 mile each way) with only a couple of steep climbs to access both waterfalls. Water shoes work best. At places the trail is muddy but not horrible. We got there at 715 and there was only one other person. We had both sets of falls to ourselves. The first set of falls was HORRENDOUS for mosquitoes, and at the second set there were none. Supposedly you can cliff jump into the first set but it looked pretty risky. The second set we swam in and there is a rope swing.(there is one dangerous boulder in the water so have someone stand by it while the other person swings in so they dont hit it) When we got back to the car at 945 the parking area was full and there were many people on the trail as we hiked out. Be mindful of the local residents for noise if you arrive early.
business_description: A hiking trail through a jungle leads to this series of scenic waterfalls with pools for swimming.

text: The best! There are no signs anywhere. The trail starts on the side of some guys house and you park on a residential street. The trail is great even from the beginning. You keep going and you get to the first falls. Keep going and you end end up at the second....Wow! Climb up to the right and then down the hill and boom! Fantastic. Worth the hike, brilliant!

text:
Small waterfall accessible through a muddy trail from a neighborhood in Kapaa. No facilities, just street parking. Recommend wearing good hiking shoes because it's muddy most of the way. Do yourself a favor and pick up one of the hiking sticks people leave at the entrance! We didn't realize that's what they were for until we were leaving. Some people swam upstream of the falls but downstream looks pretty sketch.

Bug repellant saved my skin - mosquitoes were flying into the car as soon as we stopped.

text: Beautiful walk (hike) through the rainforest in the Garden Isle to reach the two falls.  The lush vegetation and massive trees is just breath taking.  The water is cool and clear and inviting as it creates pools at the base of the falls.

text: A beautiful waterfall at the end of a short but difficult trail. To get here follow Google directions to hoopi trail but stop about 50 feet before reaching the point on the map. Look for a chain link fence and an opening with a trail marker. The trailhead is located in a residential community so don't go into any homes by accident. The trail is short but hard after rainfall as it's very muddy and slippery. Wear good shoes and if you are going late a headlamp as you'll often need hands for holding on to rock. Trail is not maintained and expect to encounter a lot of downed trees. When you get to the fork, if you take the trail down you'll end up at the top of the fall but taking the trail up will take you to the bottom of the fall.

text: This is the first falls on the Hopi'i trail. It is lovely, freshwater, although steep terrain to get down to, and very challenging to get out of when jumping in. The trail before the descent is pretty easy except for a few downed trees in your way. And some rocks and tree roots. The Hopi'i Falls is closed. This is the first falls, which we loved jumping and swimming in. It is freshwater. The trail is challenging to find, as it starts off the side of a residential road. Residents do not want you to find it. There is no signage. Not to be missed. Bring mosquito repellant, goggles, a towel, and plenty of water. Wearing Tevas or Water shoes is a good idea.

text: My first thought about a ukulele shop in Hawaii is that it could just be an expensive tourist trap, but this place is anything but that! They really know their stuff, and were super helpful recommending instruments that met my needs and budget. I ended up getting a gorgeous mahogany Kala tenor uke and they helped with accessories like the case, humidifier and strings. They were even knowledgeable about how to get it back home (stateside)! I love their website - you can see videos of the guys in the shop playing various ukuleles, so you know what they sound like. Highly recommend and can't wait to go back!!!
business_description: Ukulele shop offering numerous brand-name models, including custom designs, plus accessories.

text:
Awesome spot to start the day with a nice breezy table outdoors.  There are over a thousand rooms in the Hyatt to breakfast will be super busy at peak hours.  Best to roll down early and enjoy at a leisurely pace, before heading to the beach.
The food selection is pretty decent, with all the standards you'd expect plus some tasty local items to try.  The chef in station is amazing, producing very good made to order omelettes at blazing speed to feed the army of hungry guests.
business_description: Surf 'n' turf eatery at the Hyatt Regency Waikiki Beach serving sustainable fare in a smart space.

text: Breakfast here was included in our hotel stay so I have no idea what it costs but the food was very good and there were slight variations daily so there were  a few new things to try on most days.  Its all you can eat and a wonderful way to fill up before heading out for sight seeing or other outings.  Omelette station was fairly fast and delicious, they had limited ingredients but the guy working the station let me bring stuff from other parts of the buffet and put them in my omelette.  Would recommend especially if staying in the attached hotel.
business_description: Surf 'n' turf eatery at the Hyatt Regency Waikiki Beach serving sustainable fare in a smart space.

The Green Curry is my go to. The Basil Chicken is good too. Everything else I've tried has made me happy. Though I could eat a whole Green Curry in one go, it's big enough that I usually split in half and save it for the next day. You can also get most things a la carte, then add rice on the side. text: This restaurant was my first experience with Thai food. Upon entering the building the kitchen is visible. I watched as two elderly women (grandmothers) hand mixed a giant bowl of fresh chopped veggies with their bare hands and I thought "maaaan, that's gonna be good!" I ordered the much raved "Pad Thai", and also a side of vegetable egg rolls which were served with a side of whole leaf lettuce leaves, and fresh mint with a tangy dressing. text: For those of us who live in Hawaii Kai we don't have many options so this place is OK but really would only recommend if you are in a rush and really want a average gyro.  Their gyro is the standard US crappy prefab gryo-loaf with a blah tzatziki sauce wrapped in the greasiest pita I have every seen.  The hummus is either poorly made or they are using a very bad commercial brand, it's near identical to Kafe Europa's hummus which is atrocious also.  What bothered me most though is I asked how many pita's came with my hummus and was told four though what I ended up getting was one pita cut in four pieces which was a complete ripoff.  That being said going to mark this place average as crappy gryo-loaf with horrible hummus seems standard fair for US Greek joints.

text: Was told about this amazing place and I just had to try it for myself. Decided to order takeout and I'm glad I did. The line was so long, then I realized why after eating the udon noodles with beef and tempura shrimp. For the price,  you cannot beat this place. The servings are enough for a meal and leftovers, if you prefer leftovers. It was busy but the line was moving quickly but people were constantly getting in line. Fresh noodles are prepared right in front you, taste was delicious. Would definitely recommend, however with how busy the restaurant was, there was no one paying attention to takeout orders. They were placed near an exit and if anyone grabbed them, no employee would have noticed. I walked in, and stood waiting for someone to acknowledge I was there for a takeout order. Although I saw my order,  I thought it would be a process for takeout orders and there may be, but not when I arrived. Overall, food was very good!

text: Was not my favorite but the line was massive so I guess I'm in the minority. I got the teriyaki beef. The description said that it was fried crispy beef. When they put it on the top of my noodles I could see that it was rubbery and all stuck together. I told them I didn't want it because it was not crispy and she insisted that it was crispy. Well guess what? It was definitely not crispy. I pulled it off in one big chunk and put it on my plate. My wife got the beef noodles and was also very disappointed. But like I said we must be in the minority because everyone else seems to enjoy it. I did get the Katsu chicken and enjoy that quite a bit. In hindsight I wish I had just got that. People who know noodles probably like this place, but for a guy who grew up on top ramen, this place was over the top for me.

text:
I don't get too excited for udon but this place was so raved about so we had to check it out. The line everyday is almost out the door at all hours. However, at 10am to 11am is the best time to go for the shortest wait right before the lunch rush. We were able to come here twice without much wait.

They have a good system to help the line go faster. It's a cafeteria style as you go through the line. The first step is letting the staff know which udon you want and it's quickly prepared. Grab a tray and put your udon on it and move along to all the tempura goodies.

You can pick whichever tempura you like. They also served musubi that's ready to go. You pay at the end of the line. Get your utensils and sauces on your own and grab a seat anywhere. Inside is a bit small but they make the best of the space they have.

The Nukutama udon and the Niku udon were both delicious. Very subtle and sweet taste. Portion was  just right. The udon noodles were thick and chewy. I also love the shrimp, zucchini, veggie mixed, and sweet potato. Goes great with the udon and will fill you up. Everything was relatively a good price for really good quality. Definitely a good spot to hit up if you're in Waikiki.
business_description: Guests order at the counter at this casual Japanese restaurant specializing in noodle soup.

text:
I would eat here all the time if it was in Seattle

Hands down the best, most satisfying bowl of udon noodles I ever ate.  Ever...   the noodles have this amazing toothy bite  while being slippery and light.  And the broth is something you can bathe in.  There's this awesome oil sheen on the broth that give it a hearty savoriness to it all.

For first timers, get the Kake Udon, you can't go wrong.

And the tempura is surprisingly light.  It's not like a ready gutbomb that I think of when I hear the work tempura.  Wonderful.  Make sure you get the chicken pieces.  So juicy.

text: Fast self serving type dining. Affordable and delicious. Queues can get quite long.

text: This restaurant offers great value for udon dishes.  The seating is cafeteria style and clean. The udon noodles are freshly made and delicious!  Taste the soup before adding seasoning as it is already fairly salty.  The matsubi is also made at the restaurant with timestamps so that you know how fresh they are.
