text:
We went there twice during our visit, it was delicious, we would have gone more if there weren't so many other food options to try on the island. In total it took us 45-70 minutes to wait in line, get our food and get out the door again. They are very efficient here.
Highly recommend the Curry Nikutama it was delicious! We shared the large bowl (with an extra egg) and got 3 pieces of tempura each and were stuffed. All the tempura was delicious. Still craving the curry! Love that you can add as much green onion and tempura flakes you wish, so yummy.
business_description: Guests order at the counter at this casual Japanese restaurant specializing in noodle soup.

text: Got lucky and stopped by on a Wednesday morning around 1130am and there was no line. Got the spicy egg drop chicken udon with shrimp tempura and husband got the curry udon with a potato cake. Both were delicious, curry soup had more flavor. Such a great concept of udon fast food style. Every time we walked past there was a line or else we wouldve eaten it again. Highly recommend.
business_description: Guests order at the counter at this casual Japanese restaurant specializing in noodle soup.

text: Best udon I have ever had! The texture is amazing and the broth is delicious. Service is fast and price is not expensive. To avoid the long queues, recommend going in the afternoon.

text: Worth the wait! And if you're waiting, don't complain about it. Nobody wants to hear you lol

My go tos are cold Nikutama on hot days and Curry Nikutama on hungry days.

Fountain sodas available. Overall, it's extremely hectic and the number of people make it stressfully unorganised, but it is good.

text:
No doubt Marukame Udon is a great value...dine like a king on a budget. Generally long lines out the door and that move fairly quickly...be curtious to those around you and don't sit too long to chit chat.

Order by the number for noodles that are piping hot, and then proceed to grab an assortment of tempura, musubi, and onigiri.

Noodles are made in house and you can watch the entire process as you walk by...noodle texture is just right. The broth is on the sweeter side...not my thing but still good. The curry option is also great and helps to offset a sweeter style broth.

It is harder to bring a larger group in as tables seat a max of 4 and you're not guaranteed to be able to find tables in the same area for a large party. My advice, get there before a rush.

Overall, I would make a return trip when back in Waikiki.

text:

text:
Tasty udon very famous, always bussy. Maeukame is the institution of udon in Honolulu. The long line at all hours proof it
But the line move quite fast, open at 7am close 10pm. Prices are affordable. BTW They no longer have public bathroom. It's fast-food style ordering, You order the udon then select side dishes like tempura, vegetables and etc (all fried). If you are staying in Waikiki you should try this place.

text: Wow! Amazing! This place is ALWAYS busy.  We were staying very close by and thought we would never get to try it.  They have ropes ala Disneyland to control the lines which get very very long. My husband and I were walking by at 10:05! Score! There were only a handful of people in line. You order at the counter and pay at the end then sit to eat.  This place is not air conditioned so it was super hot inside.  We just took ours to go. The steam from cooking the homemade noodles was very uncomfortable but I didn't care.  I just didn't want to sit there. Since it was so early, we ordered one large to share among three of us and it actually was plenty. We also got some tempura shrimp, mushrooms, and, of course, spam musuby. The noodles were perfect!  The broth was flavorful. The tempura was crispy and the musuby was delicious! Highly recommended!  Wait in line if you have to!  Well worth a long wait.

text:
Extremely popular udon restaurant set a couple streets back from the main strip of Waikiki.  We went for lunch as dinner is and absolute madhouse and a super long wait... for udon!!!

The food is udon and tempura, so hard to screw up for a chain which is very popular and established in Japan.  Overall, the food was tasting great and just like it tastes in Japan.

The selection of tempura was bigger that what you normally get in Japan; but it seems that this shop sells the most tempura out of all branches of this franchise; testimony to the popularity of tempura among non-Japanese? I believe so.

Make sure that you plan the table hunting well as the restaurant is crowded and if you don't send one person to find a table while you pay; you will be walking around with a heavy plate of udon and tempura among quite narrow isles...

text: Marukame Udon Waikiki is outstanding place to eat in Waikiki: taking prices in Waikiki, the meal here is very cheap. But not always cheap means fresh and tasty. Talking about the queue: it's usually long, approx. 15-20 min waiting time but it goes fast (try avoid classic lunch time or evenings). You may also need to wait for a seating inside. text:

The place can be crowded and queues can be long. To minimise waiting, I recommend: (1) come before 6pm for dinner (After 7pm, line gets horribly long), (2) decide what you want while queuing and not decide at the counter, (3) eat quickly (If you want to chat, go to Starbucks or Coffee Bean after dinner), (4) clear your own tray after your meal to make space for others, (5) leave via the back door beside the tray clearing bay to avoid congestion within the eatery

As this is a self service eatery, no tips are required. This is a typical Asian urban eatery with fast service and fast turn-around. Just order, pay, eat, go.

text:
First tried Marugame Udon at South Coast Plaza in California and loved it. One of our friends recommended us to try the original Marukame Udon in Waikiki so we waited in the line that wrapped in front of the building.

Saw that prices for the udon were significantly cheaper than in California, so we were stoked about that. The process is pretty much the same where you order your udon first, then pick out your tempura and musubi a la carte and then pay for your order.

The only big difference is that instead of adding in your own green onions after receiving your bowl, they already add it for you here. I tried the same niku (beef) udon at both locations and noticed that the amount of beef at Marukame was less than from Marugame, but I think that Marukame knew how to portion the ratio of meat to udon better.

text: This was actually the best restaurant we visited in Oahu. We tried to go multiple times at night, but the wait is RIDICULOUS.  We decided to make it our breakfast one morning since they open at 730am, and made it there by 8-830am, and had no wait. The udon is delicious.  I got the nikutama (beef) udon with a few pieces of shrimp tempura and a veggie ball tempura (add this to your udon).  It is delicious! text:
This is must go to place in Waikiki if you want to eat udon. It is a very popular restaurant with a line always snaking out the door. Don't worry about the long line, it moves fast.
The price is very affordable so if you are on a tight budget, this is a good place to go.

Ordering your food is like cafeteria style, you order your food while in line and it is made for you. They also have specialty items like tempura shrimp, tempura fried chicken, and spam musubi which you can add as side items.

Seating can be a little difficult especially if you have a big group. Most of the seating are for 2 or 4 people. However, they do have some counter style seating along the walls.

Not sure you can go wrong with anything here, but on a hot day (and there are a lot of them in Waikiki), I highly recommend the zaru (cold udon with concentrated dipping sauce). It's so refreshing and the noodles are perfect (You can watch them being freshly made as you wait in line). The tempura is spot on and the unassuming inari is actually some of the best I've had (if you have room for it all). You're gonna wanna get in this line!

text: My favorite udon restaurant in Honolulu. The main reason I like this restaurant is mostly because of the fact that it's cafeteria-based. The only main downfall to this restaurant is that you feel as if you can't stay too long and a bit rushed. So if you're looking for an inexpensive place with great udon to just eat then go, I'd say this is your best bet.

text:
I've heard of this Udon shop during our previous visit but didn't stop in because it was so crowded.

I can't stand waiting in lines because I'm impatient but did so here because of what I've heard.

I knew the place had to be good because of the long lines out the door.

On this trip, there was just a minimal line.  I say minimal, because the wait was about 30 minutes.

The line actually went quite fast and It also helped that we arrived before the big dinner rush, which came shortly

I was also worried about getting a table but in the end, we managed to get seating.  I guess I do all the worrying for the family and everyone else just goes with the flow.

The first thing we did was to place our order on the kind of Udon we wanted.  I chose a beef broth with several different types of tempura add ons.

For the side, I selected the Nigiri with plum.

To watch the noodle chefs doing their thing, preparing the many Udon bowls in the open kitchen is amazing.

The restaurant here is like a "cafeteria" in which you go down the line, first selecting the type of Udon, then making a selection of what to add with your Udon.

They have over a dozen toppings to choose from so there is something for everyone.

"In a nutshell, the Udon was very fresh and very good."

Bottom line; on this visit, we waited less than 30 minutes to get in but well worth the wait.

The food was excellent and made right in front of you and the musubi side dish was just wonderful as well.

By far one of the most affordable places to eat.

"Now for the journey back to our resort."

text:
An incredibly delicious experience.

Is there a wait here? Ya, most probably. But the line moves quickly. How the logistics work is this: you wait in line. When it is your turn, order your udon preference, and to avoid confusion, order by the number assigned to the variant. Then, take your bowl of udon and proceed down the line to the variety of tempura items and select the ones that strike your fancy. Approach the musabe rice balls and decide if you want to stuff yourself to the max, and if so, pick up a freshly made musabi. Finally, pay and you'll complete the ordering process. Grab some tempura sauce at the adjacent table and navigate to an table and tuck in.

There is FREE water available. No need to buy bottled.

The cold broth noodle is great for a hot day. All the tempura is good here, so choose whatever you like to eat.

text:
My favorite place to eat in Honolulu.  Its kind of like In-N-Out for udon noodles.  There are only a handful of menu options but they are all REALLY good.  Everything is freshly made and delicious.

My favorite is the ontama udon (cold) which has a soft boiled egg and tempura flakes on top.  Getting it cold doesn't mean ice cold but more like lukewarm.  Not getting it hot keeps the noodles a wee bit chewier.

Its cafeteria style so you order and bring your food to a table to eat.  The line often is out the door but it moves fast.  Even if the line wraps you won't wait more than 30 min and its worth the wait.

If you want to avoid the line, they have the same menu but a little note limited for breakfast.  Or come at 11am when they reopen for lunch with their full menu.

A must try! You won't regret it.

text: I really enjoyed their udon. And it is so affordable for Waikiki, too. During peak hours there's always a long line! I was lucky and only had to wait in line for about 10 or so minutes. You order cafeteria style, so take a tray first then let the employee know what you wanna order and if it's to go. They sell fried foods (tempura) which is self serve so you will have to take the white plate if you want some of that... It was my first time going there and I didn't know how to order. They have like 3 menus in the store, 2 while you're waiting outside and one when you go in as a reference when you order but no instructions on how you order. The employees didn't seem happy or concerned enough to help so lots of trial and error. It's a restaurant designed mainly for eat in, and I found the take-out route is cumbersome, though maybe that was just because I made so many mistakes. Like I asked for extra noodle, and the guy just never said anything, not even sure if he put an extra or what. It didn't matter, I just need that response like "hey we don't do that" or "okay I put an extra there". Then after the noodle guy there's the topping guy which I learned is the person you talk to if you want extra toppings. I didn't know this and the noodle guy never said anything to me about it. He just looked pissed cause I told him my whole order and the extra topping that I wanted. So I got to the register without the extra topping, and I had to ask the lady there that there was supposed to be an egg on top. They were nice enough to get me the egg, but like I said, I wouldn't have been in that predicament if I knew how to order or at least someone told me who I talk to about the toppings. But I gotta cut them slack since it's always busy there, and they probably are sick of stupid people like me. But yeah, I really would have appreciated the help and friendliness would have been nice too. But that is what you get for cheap udon I guess?

text: The valet at our hotel recommended this place, and it sounded really good, so we gave it a try. We got there around 5:15 on a Saturday evening and the line was about 10 deep outside the door (took about 20 min to start eating). They have a pretty simple menu (kinda reminds of an In-and-Out menu) where you can choose a base noodle bowl, then you just add things like musubi, tempura, etc. on the side. The broth was a hit for all four us in the family. However, my daughter, who loves soba, somen, ramen, etc. didn't really care for the thickness of the udon noodles. Similar with my son - so I ate theirs. My wife thought it was good, but said "don't really need to go there again". I really liked it. I had the "niku" (beef) one and I think the added flavor of the meat made my soup base that much better. Overall, pretty quick, really good, and i ate too much.

text: A cute and quiet 3 or 4 star hotel settled in a quiet neighbor hood with updated looks and most of the amenities  to accommodate your stay.
business_description: Relaxed, all-suite hotel offering a rooftop pool with ocean views, plus a Japanese restaurant.

text: We enjoyed our stay very much. Security staff near lobby elevator was very friendly and always up for a friendly conversation. Housekeeping staff was also very friendly and helpful. Convenient location, close to beach and stores are a short walk away. Room was very clean except for under the couch bed. Pool area was clean with a beautiful view of the beach and mountains. We were fortunate enough to have the pool to ourselves several times. Jacuzzi wasn't working when we arrived, but we called the front desk and they had someone fix it immediately. Convenient trash disposal on each floor, and bathroom was very nice and updated. Internet speed was excellent. Would definitely recommend!
business_description: Relaxed, all-suite hotel offering a rooftop pool with ocean views, plus a Japanese restaurant.

text: Had a fantastic weekend in Honolulu and was very impressed with the hotel and staff. They were always on hand to help you out. Breakfast was delicious too.
business_description: Relaxed, all-suite hotel offering a rooftop pool with ocean views, plus a Japanese restaurant.

text: Great location. Close to the beach, convenience stores, and restaurants. Nice pool and hot tub. Relaxing lounge area as well.
business_description: Relaxed, all-suite hotel offering a rooftop pool with ocean views, plus a Japanese restaurant.

text:
The only hotel I stayed in my whole time in Hawaii (Airbnb for the rest), for me the cost performance here was definitely lower. Definitely a good location, and big room. Included full kitchenette and separate bathroom and bedroom. I was informed at checkin there is a free shuttle to the Ala Moana Centre and towel rental for the beach, but only staying one night I did not utilize these services.

I found the air conditioning to be inadequate given the large room size. Since the unit was located in the living room area, I found the circulation did not reach the separate bedroom as much, leaving the bedroom a bit warm. Luckily the bedroom had a ceiling fan that helped, and I left the bedroom patio door open a bit as well.

Bed was nice a soft, great pillows. I was a bit disappointed there was not a TV in the bedroom, I wanted to relax after a long day in bed at night and watch TV, but unfortunately the TV was only in the living room.

The bathroom was the most dated part of the room, but was adequate, shower was hot and I liked the provided soaps and shampoo. I was a bit confused at how to turn on the shower, but it is one of those pull out knobs.

Since I took a photo tour the next day, I was able to iron my outfits I wanted to wear here beforehand, which was a plus.

Decent hotel, upgrades to the air conditioning would help though.
business_description: Relaxed, all-suite hotel offering a rooftop pool with ocean views, plus a Japanese restaurant.

text:
If anybody is trying to find good deals for hotels visit RoomBully.  com booked a hotel on there and they had the best rates anywhere!

Great, friendly staff! In the heart of Waikiki and minutes from the beach. Amazing amenities in the hotel.. well maintained and clean. Roof top pool with stunning views of the ocean. Will definitely rebook when i return to Honolulu.

text: We stayed here for 7 nights on our vacation can cannot fault the place.Our rooms were roomy, clean and very nicely decorated. The customer service provided by the staff was excellent. The hotel is very centrally located with easy access to the beach or main shopping street and restaurants. There is a pool on top of the building which the children enjoyed swimming in. A great experience.
business_description: Relaxed, all-suite hotel offering a rooftop pool with ocean views, plus a Japanese restaurant.

text: So. If you have a large party traveling together, or kids, etc.. this place is pretty good. Of you are sensitive to smells, or noise, look else where. This hotel is rancid with perfume. Not just the hallways, the room, the sheets, the towels, the products in the room. Very very strong perfume, and then..maybe a lot of mildew as well? The street noise is beyound loud. My one night stay there was a car alarm going off the entire time, every 10 min or so, you'd finally get over hearing the beeping, then it would start up again. The first room they gave us, the lights didn't work in the bedroom or bathroom.  we called to have it looked at an hour goes by, it's now 930 pm. We call down again, so they make us switch rooms  the Lanai is now a railing only. The pictures are decptive. Because it really does look like that, but, the finer details of rusted and stained flooring and bathroom don't show up. lt would work for some folks, especially if you're used to a lot of noise. For me, a city girl living in the country this was really not a good fit.
business_description: Relaxed, all-suite hotel offering a rooftop pool with ocean views, plus a Japanese restaurant.

I enjoyed the hike. You have two options.
1: follow the signs for the loop and look at trees and similar nature. 2: take the switchback trail down to a very small waterfall with a few small caves. It was easy for a person who can climb 10-15 flights of stairs. Just be very careful if you attempt the steep trail.

text: This was a scenic trail through deciduous forest leading to carved lava tubes and a spring. The hike smells fantastic as multiple fragrant eucalyptus trees are found along the way. There is an easy loop portion of the trail which is not strenuous in the least, but to access the lava tubes and springs requires a descent down switchbacks along a steep cliff. Bring real hiking shoes if you plan to take this latter segment, as flip flops are inappropriate and dangerous here if the trail is wet or muddy with loose groundcover. Accessing the trail by road was a bit difficult along narrow and poorly marked roads so be sure you have some extra gas in the tank in case you get lost.
business_description: Serene, shaded 1.4-mi. hiking trail through pine forest to a spring with waterfalls.

text:
Wonderful quiet and peaceful easy walk through towering trees and so many pine needles. We walked the loop then headed to the Springs trail. I went down, down, down many switchbacks to a beautiful little stream and some very interesting looking tunnels. BE VERY CAUTIOUS, these tunnels are water control for upcountry rain run off and can become active unexpectedly. DO NOT go into them or linger in front of them unless you have a death wish.
The hike down and back up is short but a good workout.
Loved the entire experience!
There are porta potties along the way and parking is along the road and somewhat limited.
business_description: Serene, shaded 1.4-mi. hiking trail through pine forest to a spring with waterfalls.

text: Since i live on the west side i have never heard of this place until today. Its a very well marked, easy pace trail. Its not very hard. Its about medium since the trail is not paved. The trees give you so much cover from the sun. The smell of the ceder trees and the cool air makes it so much fun. The only bad part was that the stream. Since it was not raining for a while the stream bes was dry. The kids and i where so excited to go swim there but it was disappointing.

text: This is one of my family's favorite hikes. The loop is about a mile and fairly easy. business_description: Hearty servings of home-style ramen is the draw at this beachside food truck with outdoor seating.

text:
DELICIOUS RAMEN

Picnic tables surrounded by food trucks gives this spot a great vibe. It was like a oasis away from the posh stores and over priced bars off the main road.

The RAMEN and SERVICE was great
- noodles were firm and chewy
- The shoyu ramen has a super kick of flavor which was addicting.
- The beefy wild was more mild in flavor which was also excellent because the garlic wasn't over powering.

text: A cool place to hear some live local artists. Speakeasy style (behind the bookcase). Weekly artists change but currently Jeff James is there on Monday's. Bartenders are nice simple fare for late bites. A good find.

text: The space itself is pretty nice and chill, but what makes it a truly great experience is all the employees. The door security is professional. The servers are friendly and very attentive. The bartenders will make you any drink you like and all of them are guaranteed to knock your socks off. The musicians in the early evenings are some of the best on the island. Love this place.

text: My wife and I stopped here to check out the whole behind the bookcase theme and were not disappointed. They had a very classy setup and the bartender made great drinks. The love music was the icing on the cake, he insisted on singing our wedding song for us even though he never had since we are here on our honeymoon. Amazing experience. If you complain about the pricing here you probably shouldn't be going out to bars in a big city period then. Well worth it.

Would visit again.

text:
I hadn't had kalbi since arriving in HAwaii a few days ago! Today was the day to change that! The windows are tinted so it's really hard to see inside and the OPEN sign was not lit so I am glad I peered in and saw two guys eating!
We aren't that hungry so shared a combo plate, the chicken katsu and the thinly sliced kalbi. The kalbi was delicious, flavorful and tender! So good! The katsu however was a big disappointment! There was a very thick layer of batter on it, the batter on both sides combined was thicker than the chicken in it!!!
The kimchi was ok and the Mac salad was actually a potato and mac salad I didn't care much for!
The kalbi was so good that even though everything else was mediocre I still thought out deserved 4 stars!

text: The free walk-up tour is very interesting, although be prepared to not see the plantation, which requires a separate appointment. Learned how coffee grows, processed and roasted, very informative and hands-on talk. The place itself is beautiful, lots of free coffee samples and freshly roasted coffee for sale.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: The free tour is very informative, not only about their product, but coffee in general. It was one of my favourite things that I did on the Big Island and highly recommend it. Their product is top notch as well, mahalo!
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text:
What a wonderful tour of a Kona coffee plantation. Our tour guides Sam and Anna that took us around the plantation on their "mules" aka off road vehicles and where amazing. We saw sheep, chickens, horses, and cows, lava tubes, coffee equipment,  and more before visiting the gift shop. Good coffee sampling,  and the chocolate covered espresso been are great. We will definitely be back.

We came back, and Sam was still there.  Another great experience with friendly staff. Met the manager Uilani, whose name means "Heavenly Beauty".  We love the chocolate covered coffee beans and chocolate covered macadamia nuts.  We really like their coffee mugs too, good size for coffee drinkers.  We will return again.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: They have a free walk-in tour every half hour that introduces to their process. They have free coffee samples and their pea berry coffee was amazing. The drive to the farm is very beautiful as well.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Sam is a great guide.  Very knowledgeable and full of information on to pass on.  It's great to see a local business doing good and doing it the right way.  Free samples of coffee and tea.  I will be ordering from them regularly.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Fantastic coffee! I enjoyed the tour of the plantation and their processing area. Everyone was very polite and answered all of our questions. Lot's of great selections of coffee at their store. 5 out of 5 stars!
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Have nice little tour on how a coffee bean is made and good understanding of different roasts. Tallest coffee Plantation on the island and nice and cool temperature. Great visit.

text: So glad we made the drive and took a tour at Mountain Thunder! After the formal tour we took ourselves on the self-guided tour of their garden trail as well. We had a great time and enjoyed the samples while shopping for souvenirs!

text: Free coffee tour I'd recommend. Store had nice selection of products and a chance to taste different coffee
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: You need to visit this coffee farm for two reasons. First, the free tour you'll get is informative and fun. You'll explore the screening and roasting facilities, and you'll learn a few facts about Kona coffee and coffee in general. Second, you can visit the shop and taste a variety of dripped coffee selections. They also have tea if coffee makes you dance.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Beautiful grounds. Take the nature walk.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: The coffe it's delicious and the give a free tour to explains the process to make a different kind of coffe that will clear all your questions about decaf and regular, blonde, expresso and more, they have different kinds of teas too
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: This place is a great place to visit to learn more about the coffee harvesting and processing.  You can purchase all of their products in a gift store also.  My 9 year old son absolutely loved the free tour that they do every hour on the hour.  They kept it interesting enough to keep my son's attention!  That's a miracle!  They also let you taste all of their coffee blends before purchase.  Although I am in the minority that doesn't appreciate coffee from Kona, this is still a great place to learn and I am glad to have stopped by!
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: My boyfriend and I stopped in here for a free tour of the plantation and also to buy some Kona coffee after seeing them on a brochure. The tour was about 30 minutes and we learned a lot! It was great for a free price! You can also pay for a tour where you go down through the coffee trees, but the free one was great as well. The coffee was delicious and I'd recommend a stop in!
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: The free tour was excellent!  I've been on several roaster tours and this one was done by the owner.  He broke down the process and did an up and close with pea berries vs. That regular stuff.  The premium Vienna roast is the most popular and in my opinion the way to go! Well worth the short drive up the volcano
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: FANTASTIC coffee and a great free tour. Just wish we would have made it in time for the tour through the fields. The tour guide was very informative and great at answering all the questions. I will definitely be coming back next time I'm on the island. Thanks for great service, all your hard work making true Kona coffee and awesome coffee samples.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Short, informative tour mostly through the roasting facility.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Really fun tour!! I learned a lot about the coffee making process. Go in the morning since it is located in the cloud forest which will become over cast in the afternoon. Fun gift shop too!!!
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Wonderful experience at mountain thunder! Delicious coffee with several different roasts available for tasting.  Complimentary tour describing the tree to cup process. Beautiful location.

text: I owned Mamalahoa Ranch which is located across the street (dead end of Hao Street,). They RUINED our peace and quiet starting with the use of a gas generator on a SUNDAY when we were all ENJOYING the peace and quiet..   Our Tennant in the farm dwelling said that when he put his cup of coffee on the railing of the Lanai..... The coffee cup buzzed.  There went the neighborhood, literally.  Liz Montrey-Bloom
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text:
We had a great time here.  The drive to get here was interesting as we got to see a few different changes in climate and vegitation.

The young lady who gave us the tour was entertaining and knowledgeable.  Well worth the time.

text: The coffee at Mountain Thunder was fantastic. Right now they only offer two types of roasts but they are working on a third one. The tour lasted twenty minutes and was informative. I would've liked to have seen the trees and the actual mining and roasting process though.

text:
If you go there for the first time, you will be amazed to see many kind of animals walking, playing around and you can feel as if in a zoo.
Actually it is for their organic agriculture to harvest good quality coffee beans. The beans are tasty without roasted deeply. You can enjoy the fascinating aroma, thanks to the animals and soils they cultivated naturally.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Though a bit on the pricey side one of the better tours on the island.  Did the  VIP tour and had 3 guides along the way which explained every nook and cranny of the plantation.   Make sure you are prepared for some steep hills though.  Can be a little wet due to its altitude, about half way through ours it rained but they provided umbrellas.  Good coffee and tea samples as well.
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: They don't go out of their way to tell you the whole thing went bust in spectacular fashion, and the new owners are barely hanging onto the name. Tour involves being shown a gnarly old bush beside the gift store, a quick trip through a building with unused machinery, past a not working roaster and ,yes, into the gift shop.... Don't bother with the drive up to the top of the mountain, you won't even get a cup of coffee!
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Fun and interesting. We did the VIP "Tour 2" durning the off season. Our guide was great and it was really interesting to see how coffee gets to your door. The family was wonderful and very polite. Look for the cats hiding and take time to look at all the plants. The son is really bringing some neat things to see. Like banana trees, and vanilla. Able to taste some berries growing in the wild. Lava tubes are a site to see. Highly recommend the VIP tour if you're going in the off season. Great to learn how nothing is waisted and the tea they harvest as well. They do have a free tour every hour from 10am to 4pm. Make sure you call ahead for the VIP tours and roaster class. Thanks Mountain Thunder from your Arizona friends!
business_description: Revered bean-to-cup Kona coffee grower plantation site with roasting plant tours.

text: Kauai has so little culinary variation, it's wonderful to have something on the island that isn't "local" or pizza or Italian.  The owner of this place was born in New Mexico, and he's brought that state's green chile traditions with him.  There's nowhere else on the island that offers anything similar to what this restaurant offers. It might not be the best of New Mexico, but it's the best New Mexico you'll find in Hawaii, hands down.

text:
My sister and I came in for brunch on a Saturday at around 2 (I believe brunch is until 3), and they said it would be about a 15-minute wait. We were fine with that, only when we were seated, the place was half empty so I'm not sure why they made us wait.

I ordered the Sausage Hash (pineapple sausage, onions and potatoes, served with two Eggs "any style"). I was a little iffy about the pineapple sausage because I'm not normally a fan of anything with cooked pineapples in them. But I'm glad I got this. Instead of sausage with chunks of pineapple, it was more like a sausage with a nice sweetness to it. I'm not sure I really tasted any pineapple in there but I enjoyed it nonetheless. Plus the potatoes were perfectly crispy, and they give a pretty big portion.

My sister had the eggs benedict, which she said she also liked. But she enjoyed my dish too, so much so that she said she'll order that one the next time she's back.

The only thing I didn't like was that we felt kind of rushed. I understand brunch is over at 3, but they didn't have to start mopping up the place and placing chairs on the tables while we were eating. Not exactly a relaxing experience. That being said, if you do come for brunch, make sure you come earlier so that they don't try to push you out!
business_description: Daytime cafe offering gourmet Hawaiian-influenced meals in a modern white-accented setting.

text:
This was a fun brunch spot in Kamakana Alii.  We had some confusion about whether or not they took reservations and the hostess never really cleared this up.
There was a short wait of about 25 minutes and the side walk outside is a pretty busy thoroughfare between the parking lot and the mall. It was a little annoying to have to constantly walk away and back as others needed to pass. Having pagers with a longer range, text messaging, or a specific waiting area would help.
Our table only had 3 chairs when the hostess took us to our table and so 1 of the 4 people awkwardly stood around until she brought another chair. There was another table with 4 chairs set up so maybe there was some sort of miscommunication?
Once all 4 of us were seated, the waitress came over almost immediately and didn't give us more than a minute to peruse the menu and asked for our drink order. She then left before asking our preferences on milk with coffee. When she returned with cream for all, 2 of us asked for alternatives for milk (which is specifically listed on the menu).
The food was delicious, the presentation pretty, and the menu has a nice variation for different dietary needs. I hope they only get better in the future.

text:
Wished the service matched the food!

Had breakfast here with a few friends and the service was the worse I've had in over 10 years.  We had reservations at 10, got seated at 1005.   After requesting that another employee have our server come over, she finally took our orders at 1050.  At 1125 we noticed our food just sitting in the window. I asked the server how much longer on the food and her reply was "it's sitting in the window now."   I had to acutally tell her to bring us the food sitting in the window before it got cold.  Another server ended up bring us our food.  Everyone love their food. From presentation to taste.  The only hiccup with the food was veggie crepe was ordered, but somehow had ham inside.
As I said the food was good just don't think I would return due to the awful service we recieved.  The same server had a smaller party come in 15 min after us, who ordered before us, got their food and left all before us.   Not sure if this was because she knew she would receive gratuity regardless of her attentiveness.

text:
Amazing food. Great Customer Service.
We were hesitant to try it but the food was amazing. Big quantity of food for a decent price. It's hidden in the corner of a shopping center. Definitely try it if you're in Hilo.
business_description: Thai eats, including lunch specials sourced from the chef's garden, served in a simple BYO setting.

text:
I was really hungry and we had just landed. This was close to the airport and looked like it had a decent menu. We got here and there was a bit of a wait. There was a table that got free but because there were only TWO people serving it took a really long time to sit!! I mean seriously! There was a poor couple that had been waiting way before us and someone took their order 15 minutes into OUR wait!
We finally did get seated after a painful wait. We ordered the pad kee mow with beef. Hubby wanted it hot but I'd read reviews and decided on medium. It was perfect. The noodle's were really good. We also got the pineapple fried rice which was delicious. It definitely was spiced with curry powder, something I've never had at a thai restaurant before!
After eating there was another wait for the check and a box! I don like that they encourage you to bring your own boxes though.
This would have been 4 stars but took one off because of the service!
business_description: Thai eats, including lunch specials sourced from the chef's garden, served in a simple BYO setting.

text: I have eaten at Thai places all over the world. This place remains my favorite anywhere. I come back every year. Pineapple fried rice is out of this world. Thai ice tea with coconut as well. The location is not great but it is all about the food at this place. If you go anywhere while you are in Hilo, go here.
business_description: Thai eats, including lunch specials sourced from the chef's garden, served in a simple BYO setting.

text: Read a review of this in a super critical and oddly sarcastic guidebook that was a really positive review so we gave it a go. The food was amazing. Really fresh and huge flavours. Will return.

text:
Was in the mood for something spicy and nothing I had already been to seemed appealing and then I remembered passing by this place a few time and figured I would give it a chance.  Good call.  The food was amazing and totally hit the spot for both my craving of spicy food as well as my hunger.

Since it was just myself, I stuck to just one dish.  Got the Fried Fish with Red Curry Sauce.  Unfortunately, the brown Jasmin rice was not ready yet, so I got the regular Jasmin rice.  Still good all the same, but just wanted the healthier option.  The dish was great.  It was a perfect balance of fish, vegetables, and curry sauce.  I also like it spicy, so when I requested Thai hot, it came out hot!

To go with this flavor bomb of a dish, I got their Thai Iced Tea.  It was perfectly prepared with the right amount of tea and not to much condensed milk. Had a gentle sweetness and the tea made for a perfect combination to cleanse the palate after the zesty curry.

Service was very friendly and attentive.  Atmosphere was the typical South East Asian fare and very cozy.  It seemed very popular since I did arrive at about 11:30am and it started to get very busy shortly after I sat down and ordered.

I want to go back and try it again, but not alone so that I can try more dishes and do it family style.  If you ask if I recommend this place, the answer is yes. Go check it out.

The only negative thing is the parking lot.  The main parking lot in front is very busy and their underground parking is rather awkward.
business_description: Warm, white-tablecloth eatery offering traditional Thai standards in relaxed, strip-mall environs.

text: A beautiful 300' waterfall that requires a bit of a tough hike through a muddy and rocky jungle trail to get to. At the end of mile marker 2 on the Kalalau trail follow the trail up the valley for another 2 miles to the waterfall. Enjoy a swim in the cold waters beneath although you do so at your own risk because they warn of falling rocks. Wear rugged water shoes or sandals as there are numerous stream crossings and the rocks are slippery. All in all this is an 8 mile round trip hike and can be done in 4-6 hours depending on how in shape you are.

text: This is a beautiful beach but it is not child friendly. The waves are not predictable and you could hit the rocks or catch a riptide if not vigilant. I saw a lot of people playing in the water, but I felt very anxious for them. This entire island has challenging surf on the beaches and an average of 1 person per month drowns in Kauai. It is amazingly beautiful,  but extremely dangerous. Please be careful. It is wonderful to watch the waves from the safety of the amazing beachfront restaurants.

text:
I found Kehau's Kitchen while searching for a bite to eat on a Friday night.  On Saturday the wife and I decided to eat there for lunch.  We ordered Kalua pig Super combo with Squid Luau.  I ordered Lau lau super combo also with squid Luau.  The Lau lau was very juicy and delicious, .  We both found the pulehu ribs very tasty and soft.  The poi was fresh and our server even offered the house pickled onion...so ono.  The squid Luau was made just the way my grandpa makes it.  I'll be back.

If you are looking for authentic Hawaiian food with great service and an at home feel this is the place for you.

text: This place is unreal! Atmosphere and vibe is really cool and food was fantastic! Being an Okinawan izakaya, dishes were pretty unique and stood out compared to other traditional izakaya spots we've been to in the past. Some of the highlights were the taco rice in the stone pot, grilled beef tongue, chicken skin,  grilled pork belly, and hamachi carpaccio. My favorite dish of the night had to be the seared saba (mackerel) sashimi, which was torch seared on the outside, and had an amazing smoky flavor with a touch of lime. One of the best dining experiences I've had in a while, I'll definitely be back soon!

text: A gem of a find in my neighborhood! Adequate parking, charming interior, sleek and groomed servers who were unfailingly attentive and efficient. The small dishes of Okinawan treats were very good to excellent. Enjoyed the incredibly fresh and bright Hamachi carpaccio, mizuko seaweed, the  smoky grilled eggplant was a revelation and their famous peanut tofu. The goya champuru with egg tofu and spam was done very nicely for what it was. The chicken and avocado was a nice combination. They have an impressive selection of shochu and Western libations. Too full to try either of their 2 dessert offerings!

text:
So fabulous we came back twice during our visit to the Big Island! I had the perfect tuna melt both times, my mother had the pork and brisket and we paired our entrees with the German Reisling that is perfect. Do order the catch of the day on the side if not your main, it's not to be missed and was divine. Cheers to the fantastic staff and beautiful location as well. Come here before a hike in the Rain Forrest or after Kona coffee tasting. We could only do lunch as dinner was booked up in advance, make reservations if you can!

Mahalo and Aloha for the memories, Holuakoa staff!
business_description: Farm-to-table American cooking with an organic bent served in garden environs, plus a coffee shop.

text: Outside sitting area. Great friendly service. Food did not disappoint. Fresh local fish, meat and vegetable. Loved the lillikoi cheesecake.
business_description: Farm-to-table American cooking with an organic bent served in garden environs, plus a coffee shop.

text: We really enjoyed lunch here. The food was healthy and delicious. Unique menu with lots of great options. Pictured is the salad with fresh fish of the day (Ono) and the falafel plate. Fish was perfect. Incredible falafel balls, different (and better) than any we've ever had. Staff is friendly and chill. Outdoor covered seating was perfect.
business_description: Farm-to-table American cooking with an organic bent served in garden environs, plus a coffee shop.

text: This hidden gem serves fresh and upscale food. Always get reservations, they are usually quite busy. Check out the weekend brunch for yummy specials, and get serenaded by coqui frogs at night time. The casual cafe has a limited menu and drinks, and is popular with locals..
business_description: Farm-to-table American cooking with an organic bent served in garden environs, plus a coffee shop.

text: The food was good - all fresh and delicious - but points lost on service. Had to ask for salt and pepper, and cream and sugar for the coffee. The toast came dry, missing the "butter and assorted jellies". Servers were hard to flag down. Took 20 minutes for the check. Despite the yearly event taking place outside their door they were understaffed for the crowd wanting to dine there.
business_description: Farm-to-table American cooking with an organic bent served in garden environs, plus a coffee shop.

text: We love Holualoa Gardens, local, seasonal fresh produces, cooked to perfection especially the fishes in a magical garden.  If you are visiting our beautiful island this is one restaurant you should make sure you eat at.  Further more the owner and his team volunteer with local children schools to teach the future generation how to eat, grow, cook local, seasonal, fresh produces.  A great business doing wonderful things for the community, the kind of business that will always get my family support.

text: An all day affair - we arrived a little before 11 am.  I ordered the 3 egg fritatta.  It took more than 30 minutes for my food to arrive.  Our server said nothing to us about the delay until I asked if she would check on my food.  While the food itself was delicious, the delay, lack of communication, and failure to offer a little something to carry us over while we waited for our food really turned me off to this restaurant.  Further, it took another 20 minutes to pay for our meal.    If you choose to eat here,  don't arrive hungry and plan to spend a few hours.  I think it could be a lovely place to lounge for hours enjoying food and beverages if you have no where else to be that day.

BEST KOREAN FOOD IN WAIMEA!!!

text: This place is tucked away in a little shopping center in Waimea near the KTA. The menu is well-rounded and includes specials that are hand written somewhere near the register. I'm a fan of Korean food and this is decent Korean food. The kimchi and dumplings (or mandoo) are great. They even carry some Hawaiian staples like tempura purple sweet potatoes. The staff and owners are very friendly and there's even free barley tea if you decide to dine in. Have eaten here a few times during my 7 week visit and would highly recommend.
business_description: Family-owned Korean and Hawaiian-inspired fare in a casual setting with family-friendly seating.

text: Best Korean Food EVER! The chef's wife is vegan so they have delicious vegan options that are still authentically Korean. This chef knows what he's doing! Everyone behind the counter was nice, and the complimentary caffeine-free barley tea hits the spot just right on a cool day.

text:
I used to frequent this location a lot when I worked on Schofield and would travel home to Ewa.  I would mobile order when I left work so that it would be ready once I got there.

I think 4 out of 5 times they got my order wrong.  It would be ready, but wrong.  Sometimes it wouldn't be soy, or it would be mocha instead of white mocha, or hot instead of iced.  The crazy part about it is that it says exactly what it should be on the label... it just wasn't right.  And this place isn't crazy busy compared to places like Waikele, Waikiki, or Pearlridge.  To me, its just carelessness.  They don't take the time to fully read and verify.

A couple times I went home and my husbands drink was wrong but by then it was too late.  So I started checking while I was there and had them correct it on the spot.  Most of the time, they would correct it on the spot.  Sometimes they would put my cup at the end and make me wait (might as well, right, they already got my money).

I don't know man.  I worked at Starbucks before so I get it.  But still...

text: Our dinning experience was ruined by our server.  He was very pushy and seemed not very happy when we did not order alcoholic drinks.  When asked him about ingredients in certain dishes he had a very rude response and almost annoyed that we were asking.  We ask because my daughter had food allergies.  On top of this I had a cockroach run over my foot while eating..  When we brought it up to the server he just brushed it off.  Only another server came over with a broom and bin and tried to catch it and take it away.  We were guest at the Grand Wailea and we really tried not to let this experience take away from the resort.  The food was good and we really have no complaints.  We just expected so much more being an on site restaurant at the Grand Wailea.  Tip: If you come eat here around 5-6 pm you can catch the beautiful sunset from this restaurant which has an amazing view.  The service is exceptional at the resort  and we had nothing but really amazing staff during our stay.  Just this one individual ruined our night.
business_description: Private poolside cabanas are optional at this open-air Californian spot at the Grand Wailea Hotel.

text:
JAWZ Taco Truck is located in the Makena Beach (Big Beach) parking lot.  Offering a decent sized menu including tacos, burritos, quesadillas, taco salad, nachos, dogs, organic smoothies, shave ice, ice cream treats, and cold drinks.

My wife and I purchased the tacos and an organic smoothie.  The tacos were filling, tasty, and loaded with lots of cheese!  The smoothie was ice cold and refreshing.

Depending on the time of day, they can be somewhat busy and wait times may be  a little long, but I would not hesitate to purchase food from JAWZ the next time I'm at Makena Beach!
business_description: This taco van is one of a few in a local chain known for no nonsense Mexican street food.

text:
So, I lived in Maryland for a while, and occasionally I get a craving for crabs, shrimp, etc. I heard about this place a while back and had completely forgotten about it. Today, when that craving kicked in again, I remembered that I wanted to try this joint.
It was the best food decision we've made in a while.
First, the staff was super friendly and helpful.
We asked a couple of questions to get a feel of what we wanted.
My husband and I split the King Crab  Combo, and we got a pound of shrimp for the kids as well. One of my sons also got the chicken wing basket. We got the cajun and garlic butter seasoning on everything.
It was AMAZING!
It reminded me of Maryland.
We will definitely be returning.

text:
Let me say this first. This restaurant used to be my to-go place for crab and other seafood. And they also have very yummy new york steak for lunch only. It was one of my favorite.
It has been quite a few months since I ate there the last time. I don't remember it ever being so horrible. The steak looked smaller than ever and had absolutely no flavor. I ordered spice level volcanic with garlic butter to go with my seafood. The bag came with barely any sauce in it let along volcanic. There was barely any spice! I usually scoop all the sauce from the bottom of the bag and put it in my rice. And i could barely scoop any this time. I also found few blanken shrimp mixed in there. See photo attached. You'd think if they see spoiled ones they at least have the decency to take it out? Nope, just put them in anyways and hope I don't notice them.
The best thing about that experience is the popcorn chicken and cajun fries. AT A SEAFOOD PLACE!!!
Will not come here again. This place used to be great! It's a shame to leave it. You guys need to go back to how you used to manage this place. I'll look for another place for crab in the meantime.
business_description: Casual, sparsely decorated venue for a seafood menu with a Cajun-meets-Asian twist, plus beer.

text:
First impression wasn't the best. Was met with a greeting then being told they were out of half of the seafood on their menu. At 11:15 am. Tell me how a SEAFOOD RESTAURANT is out of seafood. 15 MINUTES AFTER OPENING.
After ordering some fried oysters with Cajun fries, the waitress brought out some condiments. This seems like a very easy thing that you can't mess up right? I mean it's ketchup, ranch, and tartar sauce. It's premade in a factory far far away. But these were obviously very old and left in open cups in a fridge. The tartar sauce was hard and yellowing, and very frozen. The ranch had old dried red sauce on the lips of the cups like they had been reusing them.

But wait, there's more dissapointing material coming;
The oysters. One of the very few options they had left, were HORRIBLE. The absolute worst I have had in my entire life.
I will suggest to all I meet, to never go to the Cajun King in Aiea. I wouldn't wish this on an enemy much less a friend.

text:
When we stopped at the Wahiawa Panda Express tonight it was really packed both inside and at the drive-through window.  I guess a lot of people celebrated Valentine's Day with Panda Express food.  Haha.

My husband and I had to drop folks off at the airport tonight and we never celebrate the holiday on the day of because every place that serves food is normally super busy.  Despite that, the food tonight was excellent.

I ordered orange chicken, beef broccoli, and Beijing beef.  My husband ordered beef with green beans and honey walnut shrimp.  The food must have just been made because the orange chicken and Beijing beef were crispy on the outside rather than soggy.  I would have given them 5 stars except they ran out of brown rice and the steamed veggies had to be made and I waited for the new batch to come out since there wasn't enough for the two plates I ordered.

That aside the food was good.  We love Panda Express and will probably eat here for the rest of our lives because of that.
business_description: Fast-food chain for Chinese standards, including some health-conscious options.

text:
When I first arrived, I was waiting for my friend before signing in for a table.  The greeters kept checking on me and then asked me to sign in. After signing in, my friend arrived and we waited to be called.

4 customers were called in to be seated and I finally spoke up and asked about our turn. The greeter said she just came on duty and didn't know. Didn't know what? Wasn't she checking the sign in list to realize my name was not checked off?

We were taken in right away and seated, and she did offer her apology.

The service was normal. The server was pleasant. The food was as expected.

text:
I usually get the same thing at any Panda's I go to.  I always get noodles, orange chicken, honey walnut shrimp, and cream cheese ragoons.  The great thing about Panda's is that no matter where I am, the food always tastes the same.

I can never find orange chicken that tastes quite like theirs.  Its this perfect combination of sweet, salty, and tanginess.    The honey walnut shrimp is awesome because its kind of like shrimp canton but with a more milder flavored sauce and the walnuts give it the right amount of sweet and crunch.  As for the cream cheese rangoons...I dont know what it is about it, but I just love them.  The creaminess with the crunch of the fried won ton gets me every time.  Honestly, its so lame, but its so yummy!

Nothing here ever blows me away and nothing is good enough that it makes it to the top of my list of things to eat when I need a quick meal.  BUT... it does make for some great comfort food.
business_description: Fast-food chain for Chinese standards, including some health-conscious options.

text: The service was really bad, and the food was mediocre at best. Im pretty sure we were the only table that didnt have someone come by on a regular basis. When we were sat, the hostess for some reason removed one of the sets of chopsticks from our area, even though there were four of us. He seemed surprised when I asked for them back. My son and I sat without a drink for most of the time, and our waitress only came twice to see what we wanted to order that wasnt on the Conyer belt, and once we had to walk over to the waiter. The calamari was so dry and salty that in was almost inedible, but we ate it because they charge per plate of food left over, on top of the 45.00 per person. My daughter and I wanted cheesecake, we were brought out two nearly frozen pieces. I sliced mine thinly myself to even be able to eat it. There wasnt much variety coming along the belt, and the one overworked waitress clearly couldnt keep up with the amount of people inside. Honestly the sample I tried at Sams club last weekend was better than anything they had available.

text: We love coming here for what we call "Maui-Mex." I get the Wiki Shrimp taco and add the pineapple salsa from the salsa bar. (Yes, they have a salsa bar!) We also love their BBQ pork taco. text:
I've been going to Maui Tacos for years.  I think this is one of the original locations. They recently expanded and now have more seating space and serve alcohol now.

Overall the food is fantastic. I give the food 5 stars. Portions are great and everything is well prepared. The price though seems rather steep. I guess I got spoiled because I used to be able to bring my family here for a meal.  That's no longer the case as a local family this is an expensive treat.

If you're here on vacation though I recommend you have a meal here. This is not authentic Mexican food by any means and it's not completely infused with Island flair. But it's a good meal and you will enjoy it.
business_description: Counter-serve chain restaurant that blends simple Mexican dishes with Hawaiian flavors.

text: Technically I was on the Pu'u Manamana hike which starts 30ft north of the crouching Lion Trailhead and looks at and can access the crouching Lion higher up. Views from this hike are incredible. This has been my favorite hike on O'ahu so far. The trail is a bit rough and very steep. It would be very slippery to the point of being dangerous on a rainy day. I would also not go up on super windy day as there is a chance of being blown off. Very beautiful hike, just be careful. Also note I did not do the full loop of Pu'u Manamana; just stopped when I got to the top and the trail started heading further inland.
business_description: Short, steep climb through thick vegetation to a rock formation with views over Kahana Bay.

text: View was incredible up there, definitely worth the trec. Do be aware it does get quite muddy when it's been raining. Shorter hike about a half mile or so up I believe. Recommended downloading the AllTrails app to find the opening of the hike and where you should park

text: Great short hike. You have to enter past a sign stating to not continue and warning you of the risks, but after that it's a quick 30-40 minutes to the top which provides amazing views. Would recommend for anyone comfortable with heights and discourage anyone with young children not used to hiking near cliffs.
business_description: Short, steep climb through thick vegetation to a rock formation with views over Kahana Bay.

text: Amazing views!! This hike is not too difficult, however steep on a few parts if you take the trail going up on the most east side of the entrance. I ended up climbing the western most trail unknowingly and had to scale up the side of the mountain. Be careful on this hike you will be climbing on certain parts, although the easier trail has a rope for assistance, the route i choose did not.  You will be walking on a ridge and the winds can blow at times making it interesting.  Wear good shoes and take water. It is a shorter climb then others but there is a cliff you will be walking along side. The memorials are a testament to how dangerous these hikes can be. Probably not a good hike to bring a dog on.

text: Incredible views BUT it is not a easy hike. It is very steep and not for people scared of heights. Get ready for your shoes and clothes to get muddy. Have to stay low. We went there after it had  rained and that made it way harder. Probably our most memorable experience in Oahu. Thank God no one was hurt...I was very worried. We parked at Swanzy beach park and walked. There is parking available that is way closer to where the hike begins as we had to walk 20 minutes just to get to the start. But the advantage was that we could wash and clean up before getting on our rental car.

text: There are a few different paths up to the ridge. The most popular path usually has pink flag ties on branches fo direct the way. The ridge is easy to traverse, the only concern is to be careful on the peaks and cliffs. The cliffs in particular have loose gravel which can cause slippage and pose risk. Just be careful and consider each step. The views are spectacular with far panoramic views.
business_description: Short, steep climb through thick vegetation to a rock formation with views over Kahana Bay.

text: A beautiful and rewarding hike.  Could take around 1-1.5 round trip depending on your pace and how long you wanna seat and enjoy the view. It can be a bit risky, but as long as you watch your steps and make your movement carefully, you are good. Get ready to crawl on all four at times. The view is breathtaking. The pictures do not tell the whole story, you have to experience it for yourself. There are two entry points (that I know of). One is where they have the "no entry" signs and a 2nd non official patch (marked by pink ribbons on branches) about 50 meters north along the road from the signs. I would suggest going up the 2nd path and down the 1st one.

text:
Came for lunch and it was pretty tasty.  Unfortunately the service wasn't all that great - our waitress seemed a little confused and a little dazed.  It was a Thursday at 12:30pm - it wasn't very busy but our service was very slow.  I ordered the avocado shrimp salad and it was okay.  The avocados were fresh, but the shrimp they used looked and tasted like cocktail shrimp you can buy frozen from Costco.  They didn't taste fresh, and they had a rubbery texture to them when you bit into them.  Their bread on the other hand is very delicious!  I wouldn't recommend this spot for large parties of 6 or more, they don't really have the tables to accommodate such a large party size, but anything less seems like a good idea.
Just a heads up, this restaurant is definitely catering the Japanese tourists, the menu can be read entirely in Japanese, with some small English subtitles.

text:
Hawaii's restaurant scene is top-notch and only continues to get better but why oh why is it so hard to find a great restaurant with great food and reasonable prices open on Sunday night? And, especially one that is friendly to both vegetarians and meat lovers..? Sigh.

My vegetarian friends were visiting from the mainland and we decided Arancino would be the right place for us. I like this area of Waikiki because the restaurant is on a short side street and you don't have to drive deep in the mix. The restaurant offers validated parking in the Bank of Hawaii lot which is perfect since i drive a tank and the lot has wide-enough stalls.

The restaurant doesn't take reservations and I knew there would be a wait so our party agreed on meeting early - we got there at about 5:45 and were seated by 6:30. We could've maybe grabbed a quick drink at Yardhouse but instead, we decided to kill time with a leisurely walk around the block and popped into a couple stores on Lewers St. When we made it back, we waited only about 10 minutes and our party was ready to be seated.
My BF and I split the spaghetti con tobiko e calamari and pizza peperoni e salsiccia.Both were fantastic! I loved the crunch the tobiko added to the dish, and the pizza crust was beautifully crispy.

Our table finished by sharing the panna cotta which was the happy ending to a perfect meal with friends. Vegetarians and Meat Lovers were both satisfied.
business_description: cozy Italian pizza and pastas
